window.TPP_DAILY=window.TPP_DAILY||{};window.TPP_DAILY["twos"]={"aug":{"theme":"Welcome to Our Den","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Our New Den","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Tour Our Den","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Home Den Tour","d":"Walk room to room together and name each one — “kitchen… bathroom… your room.” Naming familiar places grows new words and helps your two feel like the whole house is theirs."},{"t":"My Special Spot","d":"Let your child pick one cozy corner and pile in a pillow and a favorite toy. Having a spot of their very own builds that safe, I-belong-here feeling."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Walking Feet","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Walking Feet Game","d":"Practice “walking feet” down the hallway, then tiptoe feet, then stomping feet. Switching on your cue builds listening and body control — the same skills school will ask for."},{"t":"Tape Trail Walk","d":"Stick a line of masking tape across the floor and walk it like a balance beam. A few wobbly minutes on the line builds balance and quiet focus."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count One","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"One Cup, One Spoon","d":"Set the table together, saying “one plate… one cup… one spoon” as each lands. Number 1 is our number this month, and helping hands love a real job."},{"t":"Find Just One","d":"Ask for “just one sock” from the laundry pile, then one shoe, one block. Stopping at one is trickier than it sounds — and it plants the idea of how many."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Circles at Home","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Circle Hunt","d":"Wander the den finding circles — a plate, the clock, a doorknob. Touch each one and say “circle.” Spotting shapes in real things is how shape words stick."},{"t":"Big Red Circles","d":"Hand over a chunky red crayon and draw big circles together, round and round. Red is our color this month, and those big arm swoops are early writing practice."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Books in Our Den","domains":["Social Studies","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Cozy Book Den","d":"Drape a blanket over two chairs, crawl in with a picture book, and read together by flashlight. A cozy reading den makes books feel like a treat, not a task."},{"t":"Family Photo Story","d":"Scroll photos on your phone and name who is who — “Grandma… cousin… you as a baby.” Talking about the people in their world is a two-year-old's first social studies."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Stick these on the fridge — tiny moments that make home feel like the coziest den around.","items":["Take a bedtime den tour and let your two lead — they name the room, you follow.","Practice walking feet, tiptoe feet, and stomping feet on the way to the tub.","Serve snack with “one cup, one napkin, one cracker” — number 1 is our number this month.","Sing the ABC song at bath time — letters A, B, and C are our friends this month."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — New Friends","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Roll & Greet","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Roll the Ball","d":"Sit on the floor facing each other, legs wide, and roll a ball back and forth. Say “hi” every time it arrives — back-and-forth is friendship practice in disguise."},{"t":"Stuffed Animal Hello","d":"Line up the stuffed animals and shake each paw — “Hello, Bear. Hello, Bunny.” Greeting soft friends first makes greeting real friends feel easier."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Name Songs","domains":["Language & Literacy","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Sing Your Name","d":"Tuck your child's name into a favorite tune and sing it while you tidy or ride in the car. Hearing their own name in song lights twos up like nothing else."},{"t":"Clap the Names","d":"Clap the beats in family names together — “Ma-ma, Dad-dy, Ab-by.” Feeling the parts of words is a first step toward hearing letter sounds."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"How Many Friends","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Count the Crew","d":"Set up a pretend snack for the stuffed animals and count them, touching each head — one, two, three. Touch-counting is exactly how counting gets real for twos."},{"t":"One for Each Friend","d":"Pass out one napkin to every stuffed friend at the pretend table. One-for-each is early math, and playing host makes a two feel wonderfully big."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Squish & Share","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Play-Dough Trade","d":"Give each of you a ball of play-dough and poke, pat, and squish side by side, then trade balls. Playing next to you is real friend practice at two — and a trade is a big deal."},{"t":"Red Dough Circles","d":"Roll play-dough snakes together and curl each one into a circle. Notice out loud how the dough stretches and squashes — red circles, right on theme."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Hello, Neighborhood","domains":["Social Studies","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Wave Walk","d":"Stroll the block and wave hello to neighbors, the mail carrier, the trash truck. Naming the friendly people around us teaches twos that their world is full of helpers."},{"t":"Friend Book Snuggle","d":"Snuggle up with any book about friends and pause to ask, “Who's your friend?” Reading together every week is the single best school-prep there is."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Friend-making starts at home — here are four little ways to practice this week.","items":["Roll a ball back and forth at least once a day — say “hi” with every roll.","Sing your child's name into a favorite tune while you cook or drive.","Count the stuffed animals at bedtime, touching each head as you go.","Wave to one neighbor or helper on your walk and name them together."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Rules & Routines","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Clean-Up Time","domains":["Approaches to Learning","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Clean-Up Song","d":"Sing “clean up, clean up” while you drop blocks into a basket together. The song is the secret — twos will work for a tune long after they'd quit for a request."},{"t":"Basket Toss Tidy","d":"Turn tidying into a game: toss soft toys into the laundry basket from a step away. Aiming and tossing builds big muscles while the floor magically clears."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"First, Then","domains":["Language & Literacy","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"First-Then Talk","d":"Narrate little routines out loud all day — “First socks, then shoes. First wash, then snack.” Order words like first and then are the roots of both reading and math."},{"t":"Picture Routine Strip","d":"Draw three quick stick pictures of bedtime — bath, book, bed — and tape them low on the wall. Let your two point to what comes next; sequencing is thinking ahead."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Calm-Down Corner","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Cozy Calm Spot","d":"Build a little calm-down spot with a pillow and one soft friend, and visit it together while everyone is happy. Practicing calm when things are easy makes it work when they're not."},{"t":"Bubble Breaths","d":"Pretend to blow the biggest bubble in the world — deep breath in, long slow breath out. Make it silly and dramatic; you're secretly teaching them how to settle a storm."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Helping Hands","domains":["Social Studies","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"One Little Job","d":"Give your two one real family job — napkins on the table or spoons in the drawer. Real jobs, done daily, tell a child they matter to the family team."},{"t":"Wipe-the-Table Helper","d":"Hand over a damp cloth and let them wipe the table after snack, big arm circles and all. It won't be spotless, but those proud shoulders are worth it."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Day & Night","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Light & Dark Talk","d":"At bedtime, flip the light off and on and talk about it — “Dark means night. Sun means morning.” Our routines follow the sky, and twos love discovering that."},{"t":"Same-Book Bedtime","d":"Pick one book to read in the same cozy spot every night this week. The repeat is the point — a steady bedtime story routine actually lowers little stress levels."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Routines are brain food for twos — four small ones to try at home this week.","items":["Sing the clean-up song for one pickup a day — the tune does the heavy lifting.","Say “first, then” out loud through one routine: first bath, then book, then bed.","Practice one big bubble breath together while everyone is calm and giggly.","Read the same bedtime book in the same spot each night — repetition is comfort."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — All About School","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"School Skills Course","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Backpack Obstacle Run","d":"Set a mini course: crawl under the table, step over a pillow, hang the backpack on a doorknob. It's the school drop-off routine dressed up as a game."},{"t":"Cubby Practice","d":"Pick one bin or low shelf to be the “cubby” and practice parking shoes and backpack there. Twos who know where things go walk into school feeling capable."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"All About Me","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Mirror Me Talk","d":"Stand at the mirror together and help them announce, “I am two! I like trucks.” Saying who they are out loud builds the confidence school days run on."},{"t":"My Name Cheer","d":"Write their name big on paper and cheer each letter as you point — then let them point while you cheer. That first letter is about to become their favorite."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Sort It Out","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Red Crayon Sort","d":"Dump out the crayons and sort them into two piles: red and not-red. Sorting by one thing at a time is exactly the math work twos are built for."},{"t":"Big and Little Sort","d":"Gather school-ish stuff — crayons, cups, socks — and sort big things from little things. Ask “where does this go?” and let them be the judge."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"I Love School","domains":["Social Studies","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Fridge Self-Portrait","d":"Offer a big crayon and paper and invite a self-portrait for the fridge gallery. Scribbles count — naming the picture “me” is the real milestone."},{"t":"Play School","d":"Set up school for the stuffed animals and let your two be the teacher — line up, sing, snack. Playing the teacher helps school feel like their territory."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"ABC Send-Off","domains":["Language & Literacy","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"ABC Dance Party","d":"March, clap, and stomp through the ABC song a few times — A, B, and C are our letters this month. Moving while singing helps the sounds stick."},{"t":"Kissing-Hand Read","d":"Read a going-to-school story like The Kissing Hand, then press a kiss into each other's palms to keep for later. A pocket full of love makes goodbyes gentler."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"School is coming — these four little rituals make the big step feel small.","items":["Practice hanging the backpack in one spot every day — home cubby, school habit.","Cheer the letters of your child's name once a day, pointing as you go.","Sort the crayons into red and not-red at the kitchen table — quick and mighty.","Trade palm kisses at every goodbye this week and watch drop-offs soften."]}}]},"sep":{"theme":"All About Me & My Family","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — This Is Me","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Head to Toes","domains":["Physical Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Head, Shoulders Song","d":"Sing “Head, Shoulders, Knees and Toes” slowly, then speed it up until you're both giggling. Touching each part while naming it wires body words right into the body."},{"t":"Body Part Taps","d":"Call out simple cues — “touch your nose… pat your knees… wiggle your toes.” Two-step versions like “touch your head, then your tummy” stretch listening skills."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Two of Me","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Count Two Eyes","d":"Count together in the mirror: two eyes, two ears, two hands, two feet. Number 2 is our number this month, and your two comes with a built-in set."},{"t":"Trace My Hands","d":"Trace both hands on paper and look closely — same size, five fingers each, a matching pair. Comparing and noticing is baby science at its best."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Mirror Me","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Mirror Faces","d":"Make faces in the mirror together — happy, silly, surprised — and name each one. Seeing their own face light up teaches twos that feelings show on the outside."},{"t":"Paper-Plate Me","d":"Draw a big circle or grab a paper plate and let your two add eyes, mouth, and wild scribble hair. Hang the finished “me” somewhere proud."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Sss Like Snakes","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Snake Sound Slither","d":"Say “sss” like a snake and slither across the rug together. Letter S is our letter this month, and a sound you can wiggle to is a sound that sticks."},{"t":"Sock Snake S","d":"Stuff a long sock, then curve your sock snake into an S shape on the floor. Say “sss” as you trace it with a finger — the letter becomes a toy."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Me and My Story","domains":["Social Studies","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Baby Photo Story","d":"Look at baby photos together and tell the story: “You were so little. Now you're big!” Twos adore starring in their own history."},{"t":"All-About-Me Read","d":"Snuggle up with any book about bodies or growing, and pause to point to your child's own nose, toes, and tummy along the way. Books about me are the best books of all."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"This week is all about your favorite subject — your two — so keep it playful.","items":["Sing “Head, Shoulders, Knees and Toes” once fast and once slow every day.","Count two eyes, two ears, two hands at the mirror — number 2 week.","Slither and say “sss” on the way to the tub — letter S is here.","Tell one “when you were a baby” story at bedtime and watch them glow."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — My Family","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Family Names","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Who's That Photo","d":"Scroll family photos and ask “Who's that?” — then add one fact: “That's Uncle Joe. He makes pancakes.” Family names are a two-year-old's favorite vocabulary list."},{"t":"Grandparent Hello Call","d":"Video-call a grandparent or favorite relative and practice “hi” and “bye-bye.” A two-minute call builds real bonds and real conversation skills."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Big & Little Shoes","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Family Shoe Sort","d":"Raid the shoe pile and sort big shoes from little shoes. Sorting by one attribute is right-sized math for twos — and clomping in Daddy's shoes is the victory lap."},{"t":"Whose Sock Is This","d":"Hold up socks from the laundry and ask, “Whose is this?” Matching sizes to people is comparing, guessing, and giggling all at once."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Baby Doll Care","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Rock the Baby","d":"Rock, feed, and tuck in a doll or stuffed animal together, whispering “shh, baby's sleeping.” Caring for a pretend baby grows real gentleness."},{"t":"Scribble My Family","d":"Offer a big crayon and invite a family picture — you write the names under each scribble as they tell you who's who. Frame-worthy, every time."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Family on the Move","domains":["Physical Development","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Stroller Push Parade","d":"Let your two push a doll in a toy stroller or a laundry-basket “wagon” around the house. Pushing heavy-ish things is wonderful work for growing muscles."},{"t":"Orange Hunt Walk","d":"Walk the block hunting for orange — a flower, a sign, a leaf. Orange is our color this month, and looking closely at the world is science for twos."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Family Story Time","domains":["Language & Literacy","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Family Book Snuggle","d":"Read a book about families and pause to connect: “A grandma — like your Grandma!” Reading together this week plants family words deep."},{"t":"Square Family Frame","d":"Tape a big square on paper — our shape this month — and let your two scribble the family inside their “frame.” Trace the square edges together and say the word."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Family week — four tiny ways to celebrate your crew at home.","items":["Name three family members in photos each day, one fun fact apiece.","Sort the family shoe pile into big and little — then let the clomping begin.","Spot something orange on every walk or car ride this week.","Trace a square “picture frame” with one finger and say the shape out loud."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — My Feelings","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Feeling Faces","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Name That Face","d":"Make happy, sad, and mad faces at each other and name each one. Twos who can say “I'm mad” bite and hit less — the word is the safety valve."},{"t":"Feelings Book Check-In","d":"Read Your Feelings Matter together and make each face in the mirror as it comes up. Then ask, “How do you feel today?” and honor whatever answer you get."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Stomp & Float","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Mad Stomps, Calm Floats","d":"Stomp big when you call “mad,” then float slowly like a feather when you call “calm.” Feeling the difference in their body teaches twos that big feelings can change."},{"t":"Shake Then Melt","d":"Shake out the sillies with a wild wiggle dance, then melt slowly to the floor together. Practicing revving up and settling down is self-control in training."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Match the Faces","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Happy-Sad Sort","d":"Draw quick happy and sad faces on paper squares and sort them into two piles together. Sorting by one thing — happy or sad — is math and feelings talk at once."},{"t":"Face Pair Match","d":"Make two of each feeling face on paper scraps and find the matching pairs — two happies, two sads. A homemade matching game, with number 2 sneaking in."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Big Slow Breaths","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Breathe Like Bubbles","d":"Blow real bubbles with big slow breaths and watch them drift and pop. Long exhales are the fastest way to calm a little body — and bubbles make them fun."},{"t":"Cotton Ball Blow","d":"Set a cotton ball on the table and take turns blowing it across with big breaths. A soft puff moves it a little, a big breath sends it flying — stay close so the cotton stays out of little mouths."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Feelings All Around","domains":["Creative Expression","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Play-Dough Faces","d":"Squish play-dough into faces together — poke a smile, drag a frown. Building a feeling with their hands helps twos hold it a little more lightly."},{"t":"How Do They Feel","d":"Look at people in photos or picture books and wonder together: “Grandma looks happy. That baby looks sad.” Reading other people's faces is the seed of kindness."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Feelings week — little tools that turn big storms into passing clouds.","items":["Name one feeling out loud each day: “You look happy!” or “That felt frustrating.”","Do mad stomps and calm floats before dinner — thirty seconds does it.","Squish one play-dough feeling face together — poke a smile, drag a frown.","Ask “how do you feel?” at tuck-in and accept every answer with a nod."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — My Friends","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Roll & Name","domains":["Physical Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Ball Roll Names","d":"Roll a ball back and forth, naming a friend or family member with every roll — “Nana… Leo… Mama.” Names plus movement is a two-year-old's happy place."},{"t":"Sock Toss Hello","d":"Toss a rolled-up sock into a basket, calling out a friendly “hello” to someone you love with each throw. Aim grows, and so does the friend list."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"My Friend Is","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Friend Talk","d":"Help your two finish the sentence “My friend is ___” — a classmate, a cousin, the dog next door. Photos help; friendship starts with simply naming a friend."},{"t":"Teddy Tea Party","d":"Host a pretend tea for two stuffed friends and practice soft words — “please,” “thank you,” “more tea?” Manners rehearsed in play show up in real life."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count My Friends","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Finger Friend Count","d":"Name a friend or cousin for each little finger — one, two, three — then wiggle them all in a big hello wave. Counting on fingers makes friends and numbers both feel close."},{"t":"Two Crackers Each","d":"At snack, deal out “two for you, two for me, two for Teddy.” Sharing fair-and-square is number 2 practice and friendship practice in one bite."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Taking Turns","domains":["Approaches to Learning","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Timer Turns","d":"Use a phone timer or sand timer for turns with one favorite toy — when it dings, we swap. Keep turns short; waiting is heavy lifting for a two."},{"t":"Pour and Pass","d":"At the sink, take turns pouring water from one cup to another — stay within arm's reach. Watching water move is science, and passing the cup is sharing."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Friendship Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Handprint Friend Tree","d":"Press orange handprints onto paper as leaves on a drawn “friendship tree,” naming a loved one for each print. It doubles as sweet fridge art."},{"t":"Reading Buddy Hug","d":"End the week reading a story about friends, snuggled close. Pause and whisper, “You're my favorite reading buddy” — because reading together is friendship, too."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Friend skills grow at home first — four gentle ways to practice.","items":["Roll the ball and name a friend with every roll — keep the list growing.","Practice “please” and “thank you” at one pretend tea party this week.","Try one short timer turn with a favorite toy — swap when it dings.","Deal out snack “two for you, two for me” — sharing plus number 2."]}}]},"oct":{"theme":"The Great Outdoors","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Leaves & Trees","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Leaf Jump","domains":["Physical Development","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Leaf Pile Jump","d":"Pile up some leaves — or pillows, if your yard is still green — and jump in together. Big jumps build big muscles, and the crunch is pure two-year-old joy."},{"t":"Falling Leaf Catch","d":"Stand under a tree on a breezy day and try to catch a falling leaf. Watching, waiting, and reaching is science and coordination rolled into one giggly game."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Big Leaf, Little Leaf","domains":["Language & Literacy","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"Big-Little Leaf Talk","d":"Collect a handful of leaves and compare — “This one is big. This one is little.” Size words are math words, and leaves make them free."},{"t":"Brown Leaf Sort","d":"Sort your leaf collection into brown and not-brown piles. Brown is our color this month, and sorting by one thing at a time is right-sized math for twos."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Leaf Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Leaf Rubbing Magic","d":"Slip a leaf under paper and rub over it with a big peeled crayon until the leaf appears. That little gasp when the shape shows up never gets old."},{"t":"Sticky Leaf Collage","d":"Lay masking tape sticky-side up on paper and press on leaves and grass. No glue mess, and those little pinching fingers get a fine-motor workout."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"T for Tree","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"T Is for Tree","d":"Make a letter T with two sticks or with your arms — one up, one across — saying “t-t-tree.” Letter T is our letter this week, standing tall as a trunk."},{"t":"Tap the Trunk","d":"Walk to a tree, touch the bark, and tap it gently — “t-t-t.” Feeling rough bark while hearing the T sound gives the letter a home in the real world."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Under the Tree","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Blanket Book Picnic","d":"Spread a blanket under a tree and read a book together outside. Fresh air plus a story is the best kind of quiet time — for both of you."},{"t":"Share the Rake","d":"Do a little yard work together and take turns with the rake or broom. Working side by side and swapping tools is how twos learn that families are teams."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Leaf week — grab a few from the yard and the learning comes free.","items":["Collect five leaves on a walk and sort them into big and little at home.","Make one leaf rubbing with a big crayon — hang it on the fridge.","Make a T with your arms and say “t-t-tree” — letter T week.","Read one story outside on a blanket, even just ten minutes."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Bugs & Critters","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Creep Like Ants","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Ant March","d":"Creep low across the floor in a line like busy ants, then march it double-time. Moving like a critter builds body control and a busy imagination at once."},{"t":"Buzz and Flutter","d":"Buzz around like bees, then flutter slow like butterflies when you call the switch. Fast-to-slow switching is sneaky self-control practice."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Count Three Bugs","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Three Bug Watch","d":"Head outside and find three bugs — an ant, a fly, a beetle — counting each one. Number 3 is our number this month, and the backyard is full of volunteers."},{"t":"Pasta Bug Count","d":"Call big dried pasta pieces “bugs” and count three into a cup, then dump and count again — stay close while they play. Filling, dumping, and counting is toddler heaven."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Gentle with Bugs","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Quiet Bug Watcher","d":"Find a bug and watch it together without touching, whispering like nature detectives. Practicing gentle with tiny creatures grows gentle with everyone."},{"t":"Wiggly Bug Words","d":"Describe the bugs you spot with juicy words — wiggly, tiny, fast, shiny. Rich describing words now become rich sentences later."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Bug Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Fingerprint Bugs","d":"Press washable-marker fingertips onto paper to make fingerprint bugs, then you add the legs while they add more bugs. A whole garden appears in five minutes."},{"t":"Play-Dough Caterpillar","d":"Roll three balls of play-dough and line them up into a caterpillar — count them as you go. Rolling and pressing builds the hand strength crayons need."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Critters Help Too","domains":["Social Studies","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Everybody Has a Job","d":"Talk about critter jobs on your walk — bees help flowers, worms help gardens. Everybody has a job, just like helpers in our family and our town."},{"t":"Itsy Bitsy Story Time","d":"Read a bug book or do “Itsy Bitsy Spider” with all the hand motions, twice if requested. Fingerplays are stories, songs, and fine-motor work in one."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Bug week — tiny critters, big wonder, zero supplies needed.","items":["Find and count three bugs outside this week — number 3 is our number.","Practice the quiet bug watch: look closely, whisper, hands to ourselves.","Do “Itsy Bitsy Spider” with hand motions at bath time.","Roll a three-ball play-dough caterpillar and count each ball."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Weather & Sky","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Sun & Rain Dance","domains":["Physical Development","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Weather Freeze Dance","d":"Dance wild when you call “sunshine,” freeze still when you call “rain.” Stopping on cue is real self-control work hiding inside a dance party."},{"t":"Fingertip Rainstorm","d":"Drum fingertips on a cardboard box — soft drizzle, then a big storm, then quiet. Making the weather with your hands teaches loud, soft, fast, and slow."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Weather Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Window Weather Report","d":"Look out the window together each morning and report: “sunny… cloudy… rainy.” Give your two the job of announcer — same window, new news every day."},{"t":"Gray-Day G","d":"On a cloudy day, say “g-g-gray” looking at the sky, and trace a big G on a foggy window or in the air. Letter G gets its turn this week."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Clouds & Triangles","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Cotton-Ball Clouds","d":"Glue cotton balls or torn paper scraps onto blue-scribbled paper as clouds, counting to three as they go up. Fluffy art with number 3 tucked inside."},{"t":"Triangle Umbrellas","d":"Draw triangle umbrella tops and let your two add rain dots and handle lines. Triangle is our shape this month — trace its three sides and count them."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Dress for Weather","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Zip It Myself","d":"Practice starting a jacket zipper together, then let your two pull it up solo. Self-help wins like zipping fill a two-year-old's proud tank for the whole day."},{"t":"What Do They Need","d":"Play weather helper: “It's chilly — what does Grandma need? A sweater!” Thinking about what other people need is early empathy at work."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Watch the Sky","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Shadow and Puddle Watch","d":"On a sunny day chase your shadows; after rain, visit a puddle and poke it with a stick. Noticing what the sky leaves behind is toddler science at its finest."},{"t":"Sky Book Snuggle","d":"Read a weather or sky book together, then look out the window and find what matched. Connecting book pages to the real sky makes stories feel true."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Weather week — the sky changes daily, and that's the whole lesson plan.","items":["Give your two the morning window weather report job all week.","Trace a triangle and count its three sides — shape of the month.","Practice one jacket zip-up a day until it's a solo victory.","Say “g-g-gray” at the sky on cloudy days — letter G week."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Animals & Homes","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Animal Walks","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Move Like Animals","d":"Hop like a bunny, waddle like a duck, stomp like a bear across the living room. Animal walks build strength and balance while the imagination runs wild."},{"t":"J Is for Jump","d":"Jump like a kangaroo saying “j-j-jump” with every landing. Letter J closes out our month, and it comes with its own built-in action."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Who Lives Here","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Animal Home Talk","d":"On a walk, look for animal homes — a bird's nest, a squirrel hole, a spider web. Ask “who lives here?” and let the guessing run wild."},{"t":"Peek-a-Home Boxes","d":"Hide toy animals inside boxes or under cups and ask, “Who lives in this house?” Peeking, guessing, and naming is language play twos can't resist."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Match Animal Homes","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Home Match Game","d":"Set out three boxes as houses and help each toy animal find its home — bird up high, dog by the door. Matching one-to-one is early math dressed as pretend."},{"t":"Three Little Houses","d":"Build three homes from boxes or blankets and count them — one, two, three. Then count the animals moving in. Number 3 gets one last hurrah."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Care for Animals","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Feed the Toy Pets","d":"Take turns pretend-feeding the stuffed animals — one scoop for the bear, one for the bunny. Caring for creatures, even fuzzy ones, grows real tenderness."},{"t":"Little Pet Helper","d":"If you have a pet, give your two one small helper job, like holding the food scoop with you. No pet? Watering a plant counts — living things need us."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Build a Nest","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper-Bag Nest","d":"Crumple a brown paper bag into a nest and tuck in rolled-sock “eggs.” Brown is our color this month, and crumpling paper is grand work for little hands."},{"t":"Animal Sound Storybook","d":"Wrap up the month reading an animal book together, making every sound — moo, roar, tweet. Sound effects turn your two into a storyteller, not just a listener."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Animal week — every stuffed friend in the house just became a teacher.","items":["Do one animal walk to the tub each night — bear stomps recommended.","Hunt for one real animal home outside — a nest, a web, a hole.","Jump and say “j-j-jump” like a kangaroo — letter J week.","Crumple a brown-bag nest with sock eggs — brown is our color."]}}]},"nov":{"theme":"Thankful Hearts","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — I Am Thankful","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Thankful Stretches","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Gratitude Yoga","d":"Stretch tall like a tree, then hug yourself tight and say one thing you love. Big movements plus feeling words help twos connect their bodies to their hearts."},{"t":"Happy Face Mirror","d":"Stand at the mirror together and make a happy face, a surprised face, a thankful smile. Naming feelings out loud is how two-year-olds learn to handle them."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Thankful Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Thankful Talk","d":"At snack, take turns finishing the sentence 'I am thankful for…' Keep your own answers toddler-simple — juice, hugs, the dog. Hearing you model the sentence teaches new words fast."},{"t":"Letter H Hugs","d":"Draw a big H on paper and let your child trace it with one finger, then trade hugs — H is for hug. One letter, lots of love, done in five minutes."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count to Four","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Four Blessings Count","d":"Line up four favorite things — a cup, a teddy, a shoe, a book — and count them together, touching each one. Touching while counting is how real number sense begins."},{"t":"Yellow Leaf Look","d":"Step outside and look for yellow — leaves, flowers, a door. Hold a leaf up to the light and wonder aloud what made it change. Little noticings are early science."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Thankful Tree","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Handprint Leaves","d":"Trace your child's hand on paper, let them scribble it yellow with a big crayon, and tape the leaves to a doorway tree. Their art on display says their work matters."},{"t":"Rectangle Picture Frame","d":"Cut a rectangle window in a cereal-box panel and let your child decorate the frame for a family photo. Point out the rectangle shape as you go — it is this month's shape."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Read and Feel","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Feelings Story Time","d":"Snuggle up with Your Feelings Matter or any favorite book and make the faces together on every page. Ten cozy minutes of reading together beats any worksheet."},{"t":"Thank You Wave","d":"On a walk or a drive, wave and say thank you to the helpers you see — mail carrier, crossing guard, garbage truck. Twos learn community from your example."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Little thank-yous, practiced daily, grow into grateful hearts.","items":["Say one 'thank you for…' at dinner each night — grown-ups go first.","Tape a paper tree to the fridge and add one scribbled leaf a day.","Trace a big H with one finger — H is for hug, hat, and home.","Count four of anything at bath time: toes, cups, ducks, splashes."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Family & Home","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Helper Hands","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Chore Play","d":"Hand over a real job — matching socks from the laundry or wiping the table with a dry cloth. Twos glow when they help, and family jobs build belonging."},{"t":"Laundry Basket Push","d":"Load a laundry basket with stuffed animals and let your child push it room to room making deliveries. Heavy pushing is great for growing muscles and calm bodies."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"My Family Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Who Loves Me","d":"Look at family photos and name each person together — Mama, Nana, brother. Then ask, 'Who loves you?' and let your child point. Belonging you can see and touch."},{"t":"Family Book Nook","d":"Pile up pillows, pick a book about families, and read together doing the voices. Ask 'where's the baby?' and let them point — pointing and naming grows vocabulary fast."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count My Family","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Family Counting","d":"Count the people in your family on fingers, one name per finger. Then count again at dinner — one plate for each person. Matching one-to-one is big math for twos."},{"t":"Stack the Family","d":"Stack one block for each family member and name them as the tower grows, then knock it down and build it again. Repeating a job start to finish builds stick-with-it skills."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Family Portrait","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Draw My Family","d":"Offer big crayons and ask your child to draw their family — scribbles absolutely count. Write the names they say next to each scribble. Their words on paper is early literacy."},{"t":"Letter K Kisses","d":"Draw a big K, trace it with a finger, and say K is for kiss — then deliver kisses to everyone home. Letters stick when they come with love."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Home Explorers","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Rectangle Hunt","d":"Walk the house hunting rectangles — doors, books, the TV, pillows. Trace the shape in the air each time you find one. Shape talk now, geometry later."},{"t":"Kitchen Sound Test","d":"Tap a wooden spoon on a pot, a plastic bowl, the table. Which is loud, which is quiet? Comparing sounds is a real experiment, two-year-old style."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Home is the first classroom, and this week family is the lesson.","items":["Give one small daily job — napkins on the table or socks in the basket.","Count the people at dinner, then count the plates to match.","Trace a big K — K is for kiss; deliver one to everyone home.","Look at family photos at bedtime and name who loves them."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Sharing & Giving","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Pass It Along","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Pass the Ball","d":"Sit knee to knee and roll a ball back and forth saying 'your turn, my turn.' Short, playful turn-taking is exactly how sharing starts at two."},{"t":"Teddy Delivery Walk","d":"Have your child carry a stuffed animal across the room to give to someone, then trot back for another. Giving feels good, and all that toddling burns happy energy."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Kind Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Please and Thank You","d":"Play a simple hand-it-over game — they ask 'please,' you hand the toy, they say 'thank you.' Swap roles. Manners practiced in play show up at the table."},{"t":"Thank a Helper","d":"Help your child say thank you to someone who helps them today — the librarian, a grandparent, the bus driver. Watching you be kind is the whole lesson."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Share It Fair","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"One for You","d":"Share a snack out loud — 'one for you, one for me' — until the crackers are gone. Dealing items one at a time is early math hiding in plain sight."},{"t":"Two Bowl Sort","d":"Set out a bowl for your child and a bowl for teddy, and share blocks between them one at a time. Finishing the whole job builds focus and follow-through."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Thank You Card","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Scribble a Card","d":"Fold paper, hand over the big crayons, and make a thank-you card for someone who loves them. Write the words they tell you inside, then deliver it together."},{"t":"Read Then Make","d":"Read a favorite book about kindness together, then make a card for the person you thought of while reading. Stories give twos the words for big warm feelings."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Give and Wrap","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Crinkle Wrap Play","d":"Wrap a small toy in paper and let your child shake, crinkle, and unwrap it, then wrap it again to give away. Loud paper, quiet paper — that is sound science."},{"t":"Ribbon Pull Test","d":"Set out ribbon, yarn, and a paper strip and test together: which stretches, which tears, which curls? Little compare-and-try moments are how scientists start."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Sharing is a skill, not a personality — a little practice every day goes far.","items":["Play 'your turn, my turn' with one toy for two minutes a day.","Share snacks out loud: one for you, one for me.","Make one thank-you card together and deliver it this weekend.","Trace a big L — L is for love; name the people you love."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — A Thankful Feast","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Set the Table","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Table Helper","d":"Let your child carry napkins and plastic cups to the table one trip at a time — two hands, walking feet. Careful carrying is real coordination work, and helpers feel proud."},{"t":"Placemat Rectangles","d":"Make placemats from paper rectangles and let your child set one at each seat. Family jobs teach twos that everyone at home pitches in."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Harvest Foods","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"H Food Tasting","d":"At a meal, name foods that start with H and say the sound together — h-h-ham, h-h-honey. Then smell and taste and find words for it: sweet, warm, crunchy."},{"t":"Feel the Food","d":"Before cooking, let your child pat a potato, roll an orange, shake dry pasta in a cup. Talking about bumpy, smooth, and loud builds science words right at the counter."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count the Feast","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Plates and Cups","d":"Count out four plates and four cups together, touching each one. If one is missing, wonder aloud — 'do we have enough?' That little question is real problem-solving."},{"t":"Napkin Fold Repeat","d":"Show a simple napkin fold, then let your child try again and again until the stack is done. Sticking with a fiddly job to the end is the skill we are building."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Gratitude Circle","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"One Good Thing","d":"At dinner, everyone names one good thing from today — keep yours toddler-simple. A daily gratitude habit is linked to happier moods and better sleep, even for grown-ups."},{"t":"Thankful Book Snuggle","d":"Reread this month's favorite thankful book and pause to ask, 'what are you thankful for?' Don't rush the answer — wait time is where the language grows."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Feast Craft","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper Plate Feast","d":"Let your child scribble pretend foods on a paper plate with big crayons — yellow corn, red apples — then serve it to the family. Pretend play plus art in one."},{"t":"H K L Parade","d":"Write H, K, and L big on paper, tape them to the floor, and march from letter to letter calling out each name. Moving bodies help letters stick."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"End the month around the table — the feast itself is the lesson.","items":["Let your child set out the cups and napkins for one meal a day.","Count four things at dinner: plates, forks, rolls, or people.","Play 'one good thing' at bedtime — everyone shares one.","Finger-trace H, K, and L on the fridge each morning this week."]}}]},"dec":{"theme":"Lights & Traditions Around the World","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Lights Around the World","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Twinkle Freeze Dance","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Freeze Dance Glow","d":"Play music and dance, then call 'freeze — twinkle!' and wiggle fingers like little lights. Stop-and-go games build the self-control twos are just starting to grow."},{"t":"Flashlight Follow","d":"Dim the lights and let your child chase a flashlight dot across the floor — slow, fast, up the wall. Big giggles, big gross-motor work, five minutes flat."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Light Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Glow Shine Bright","d":"From a window or on an evening walk, spot lights and practice the words together: glow, shine, bright, twinkle. New describing words grow fastest when they are tied to real things."},{"t":"Shadow Wonder","d":"Shine a flashlight at a toy and look at its shadow — move the light close, then far. Wondering aloud 'what happened?' is the very start of science."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count the Lights","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Five Light Count","d":"Spot five lights around your home — lamp, oven clock, porch light — and count them together, pointing to each. Five is this month's number, and pointing makes it stick."},{"t":"On Off Game","d":"Let your child be the light helper at one safe switch: on, off, on, off. That back-and-forth is a first pattern, and being in charge feels wonderful at two."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Cozy Light Feelings","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Blanket Glow Nest","d":"Build a blanket nest, turn the lights low, and cuddle up with a flashlight and a book. Talk about how cozy and safe feel. Reading in the glow makes it magic."},{"t":"Warm and Safe Talk","d":"At bedtime, name what makes your child feel warm and safe — blankie, hugs, the night-light. Giving comfort a name helps twos ask for it with words instead of tears."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Lights and Lanterns","domains":["Creative Expression","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper Star Craft","d":"Cut a big star from paper — grown-ups on scissors — and let your child cover it in green crayon scribbles, then hang it in the window. People all over the world hang lights and stars to celebrate in winter."},{"t":"Hallway Glow Walk","d":"Drop a small flashlight in a paper bag, fold the top, and take a slow lantern walk down the hallway like celebrations do around the world. Careful carrying plus a little wonder."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A cozy week of glow — little lights, big wonder.","items":["Take one after-dark light-spotting walk or window watch this week.","Count five lights around your home, pointing to each one.","Trace a big W with one finger — W is for window, where the lights live.","Read one book by flashlight in a blanket nest before bed."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Family Traditions","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Tradition Dance","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"World Dance Party","d":"Try a simple dance from your family's culture or one you love — clap, stomp, spin, hands up high. Twos learn traditions through their bodies first."},{"t":"Scarf Twirl Dance","d":"Put on family-favorite music and twirl with scarves or dish towels. Music that means something to your family is a tradition your child can feel."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"My Family Does","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"We Always Say","d":"Tell your child one thing your family always does — pancake Saturdays, a special goodnight phrase — and do it together today. 'My family does this' is pure belonging."},{"t":"Tradition Story Call","d":"Video-call a grandparent or someone dear and ask them to share a favorite family tradition or song. Real faces and real stories grow language and love at the same time."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Sort the Season","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Holiday Object Sort","d":"Gather a few safe seasonal objects — cards, bows, soft decorations — and sort them one way: big and little, or green and not-green. One attribute is plenty at two."},{"t":"Count to Five","d":"Count five bows or five cotton balls into a bowl, one at a time. Then dump and count again — dumping and refilling never gets old, and neither does five."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Proud of Family","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Tradition Collage","d":"Glue photos, scraps of wrapping paper, and your child's scribbles onto one page about your family's season. Hang it low so they can show it off — pride matters."},{"t":"Family Hand Wreath","d":"Trace everyone's hands on paper, cut them out with grown-ups on scissors, and glue them into a circle to hang. Every hand belongs — that is the whole lesson."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Read and Wonder","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Traditions Read Aloud","d":"Share a book about winter celebrations around the world and linger on the pictures — 'what do you see?' Pointing and naming beats quizzing every time."},{"t":"Ice Cube Melt","d":"Drop an ice cube in a bowl and check on it after play — smaller? gone? Wonder together where it went. Melting is winter science that works in any weather."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Your family's traditions are the curriculum this week — share them proudly.","items":["Do one 'we always…' family tradition and name it out loud.","Sort seasonal objects one way: big and little, or green and not-green.","Trace a big F — F is for family; count yours on five fingers.","Call a relative and let your child say hi and wave."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Giving & Kindness","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Deliver the Gift","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Gift Delivery Relay","d":"Wrap a soft toy loosely and have your child carry it across the room to place in your hands — a gift for you. Cheer, rewrap, repeat. Giving really does feel this good."},{"t":"Sock Ball Helpers","d":"Roll socks into balls and toss them into the laundry basket together, cheering every basket. Helping plus throwing practice — a two-for-one for busy twos."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Kind to Others","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Neighbor Surprise","d":"Help your child scribble a cheery picture and leave it at a neighbor's or grandparent's door together. Small kindnesses teach twos they can make someone's whole day."},{"t":"Kindness Story Time","d":"Read a story about giving or helping and point out the kind moments — 'look, she shared.' Stories give twos pictures of what kindness looks like."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count the Gifts","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Five Gifts Count","d":"Wrap five little toys in scraps of paper and count them into a basket, one to five. Unwrap and start over — repetition is exactly how twos learn numbers."},{"t":"Share the Blocks","d":"Deal blocks out loud — 'one for you, one for bear, one for me' — until they are gone, then gather up and go again. Finishing the round builds patience and early math."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Giving Feels Good","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Make a Gift","d":"Let your child scribble a masterpiece with big crayons, then wrap it together for someone they love. Ask how giving feels — happy? proud? Name the feeling together."},{"t":"Green Handprint Gift","d":"Trace your child's hand, let them color it green, and cut it out as a little holding-hands gift for a grandparent. Handmade beats store-bought every single time."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Wrap and Discover","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Mystery Gift Box","d":"Hide a toy in a box and let your child shake, tilt, and listen before opening. Heavy or light? Loud or quiet? Guessing from clues is toddler science."},{"t":"Tape Peel Game","d":"Press strips of tape lightly on the table and let your child peel them off and stick them onto wrapping paper. Peeling tape is a serious little-finger workout."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Giving is a feeling twos learn by doing — one small kindness a day.","items":["Help your child give one small thing a day — a hug, a drawing, a shared toy.","Practice 'here you go' and 'thank you' at snack time.","Trace a big N — N is for nice; name one nice thing your child did today.","Wrap and count five little gifts in scrap paper, one to five."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Celebrations","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Celebration Parade","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Pots Pans Parade","d":"Hand out a pot drum and a wooden spoon and march through the house celebrating — high steps, big beats, and a family cheer at the end. Joy is the whole point."},{"t":"Ribbon Wand Wiggle","d":"Tape ribbon or fabric strips to a spoon and dance with big swoops to celebration music. Crossing the body with big arm swings builds real coordination."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Tell the Party","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Retell the Fun","d":"After any celebration moment, help your child tell it back: 'We danced. We ate. We clapped.' Retelling in little sentences is a big language milestone at two."},{"t":"Joy Face Check","d":"Make excited faces in the mirror together and name the feeling — happy, excited, wiggly. Big celebration feelings are easier to ride when they have names."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Countdown Fun","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Five Four Three","d":"Count down from five on fingers, then shout 'celebrate' and toss crumpled-paper confetti. Counting backward is brand-new thinking for twos — keep it silly and short."},{"t":"Star Shape Spot","d":"Look for stars together on boxes, pajamas, and book covers, counting up to five. Trace a star in the air with one finger — slow and wobbly is just fine."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Celebrate Together","domains":["Social Studies","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"World Party Book","d":"Snuggle up with a book about celebrations around the world and notice the lights, food, and dancing. 'People celebrate in lots of ways' is the gentle takeaway."},{"t":"Family Milk Toast","d":"At dinner, raise cups of milk or water and clink to something happy from this year. Little rituals like a toast teach twos how families mark special days."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Letters and Sparkle","domains":["Creative Expression","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Letter Flag Garland","d":"Write W, F, N, and O on paper flags, let your child decorate each one, and string the garland where they can see it. Say each letter name as you hang it."},{"t":"Shiny or Not","d":"Sort kitchen foil scraps, paper, and safe decorations into shiny and not-shiny piles by holding each up to the light. Noticing how light bounces is real science play."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Finish the month celebrating — joy, togetherness, and one last countdown.","items":["Count down from five and toss paper confetti — then count while cleaning up.","Raise a milk toast at dinner to one happy thing from this year.","Trace a big O — O is round like the moon; find round things at home.","Hang your child's letter garland — W, F, N, O — and say each one."]}}]},"jan":{"theme":"Winter Wonders","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Snow & Ice","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Ice Skating Fun","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper Plate Skating","d":"Set paper plates under your child's feet on carpet and skate across the room with slow, careful slides. Balance work disguised as winter magic."},{"t":"Snowflake Twirl","d":"Put on soft music and float like snowflakes — twirl, drift, and melt into a heap on the floor. Fast-then-slow movement helps twos practice calming their bodies."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Cold Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Ice Cube Touch","d":"Hold an ice cube together and find the words: cold, wet, slippery, brrr. Watch it melt in a bowl and wonder aloud where it went. Words plus wonder equals science."},{"t":"Snowy Book Time","d":"Read The Snowy Day or any wintry favorite and act out the crunch-crunch walking together. Pausing to move like the story keeps two-year-old listeners hooked."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count Snowballs","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Six Snowball Count","d":"Roll six snowballs from crumpled paper or rolled socks and count them into a bowl, one at a time. Six is a big number for twos — little hands make it real."},{"t":"Snowball Stack Try","d":"Try stacking the paper snowballs into a tower — they will tumble, and that is the fun part. Trying again after a topple is the skill we are really building."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Cozy Calm Feelings","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Cozy Corner Nest","d":"Build a cozy corner with pillows and a blanket and practice going there to feel calm. Name it together: 'this is our cozy spot.' A calm-down place beats a time-out."},{"t":"Warm Cold Talk","d":"Sort a few things by feel — a blanket is warm and cozy, a spoon from the fridge is cold. Naming how things feel builds the words twos need for feelings too."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"My Kind of Winter","domains":["Creative Expression","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Cotton Ball Snowman","d":"Glue cotton balls or torn paper onto a snowman shape and add a scribbled hat with a big crayon. If you live where it never snows, this is your snow — no mittens required."},{"t":"Winter Where We Live","d":"Look out the window and talk about winter where you live — do we wear coats or flip-flops? Some kids sled, some swim. Different homes, same wonder."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Snow or sunshine outside, this week is full of cool wonders.","items":["Hold an ice cube together and find three cold words: cold, wet, slippery.","Count six paper snowballs into a bowl, one at a time.","Trace a diamond shape with one finger — this month's shape.","Read one snowy book in a blanket nest this week."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Winter Animals","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Animal Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Waddle Like Penguin","d":"Waddle like a penguin — say p-p-penguin as you go — then lumber like a bear and dart like a fox. You call the animal, your child does the move. Pure gross-motor joy."},{"t":"Hibernation Den","d":"Drape a blanket over two chairs and hibernate like bears — crawl in, snore loudly, wake with a giant stretch. Pretend play is a two-year-old's best thinking."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Animal Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Winter Animal Book","d":"Read a book about winter animals together — Over and Under the Snow is lovely — and talk simply: bears sleep, penguins slide. One new fact is plenty at two."},{"t":"Animal Sound Game","d":"Make winter-animal sounds and let your child guess and copy — owl hoots, wolf howls, quiet bunny sniffs. Listening closely and copying sounds builds early phonics muscles."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count and Sort","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Animal Sort","d":"Gather the stuffed animals and sort them one way — big and little, or soft and not-soft. Sorting by one attribute is exactly right for this age."},{"t":"Count the Critters","d":"Line up six stuffed animals for a pretend winter march and count them, touching each head. Then count again in a different order — still six, and that is the discovery."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Gentle With Animals","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Gentle Hands Practice","d":"Practice gentle pats on a stuffed animal — soft, slow, gentle. If you have a pet, practice together with your hand guiding theirs. Gentleness is taught, not assumed."},{"t":"Teddy Bedtime","d":"Have your child tuck a teddy in for winter hibernation — blanket, pat-pat, whisper goodnight. Caring for a lovey rehearses empathy in the sweetest way."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Animal Helpers","domains":["Social Studies","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Feed the Birds","d":"Scatter a little birdseed or dry oats outside a window and watch quietly for visitors. Helping hungry winter birds is a first lesson in caring for the world."},{"t":"Vet Helper Play","d":"Set up a pretend vet clinic — check teddy's ears, wrap a hurt paw in a sock. Talk about how vets help animals. Helper play grows big-hearted kids."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A week of waddles, growls, and gentle hands.","items":["Waddle like a penguin down the hallway — say p-p-penguin as you go.","Sort stuffed animals one way: big and little, or soft and not-soft.","Practice gentle pats on a teddy: soft, slow, gentle.","Tuck a teddy in for winter hibernation at bedtime."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Staying Warm & Cozy","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Dress for Winter","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Get Dressed Race","d":"Lay out a hat, jacket, and shoes and cheer your child through putting them on — help with zippers and the last stubborn shoe. Self-dressing is huge independence work at two."},{"t":"Two Step Dressing","d":"Give a two-step direction: 'get your hat, then bring your shoes.' Two steps is the sweet spot for this age — celebrate big when both steps land."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Warm Dry Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"D Word Day","d":"Say the D sound together — d-d-down, d-d-dry — while patting a puffy jacket or a fluffy dry towel. Sounds stick best when little hands are touching the words."},{"t":"Wet Dry Test","d":"Dip one sock in water, keep one dry, and let your child feel both. Which would keep you warm? Wet-and-dry is a real experiment with laundry-basket materials."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Match the Mittens","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Mitten Match Up","d":"Mix up gloves, mittens, or socks and match the pairs together — 'these two go together!' Matching pairs is early math your child can do right in their lap."},{"t":"Bundle Up World","d":"Look at pictures of children in snowy places — big coats, boots, scarves — and compare with what you wear at home. Same kids, different weather, all staying cozy."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Warm and Calm","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Calm Cozy Reading","d":"Pile the blankets, dim the lights, and read together in your coziest voice. A calm-down cuddle with a book teaches twos that quiet time feels good, not boring."},{"t":"Blanket Burrito Hug","d":"Roll your child gently in a blanket burrito with big slow squeezes — always face out, always giggling. Deep pressure is wonderfully calming for busy little bodies."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Design a Mitten","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Mitten Masterpiece","d":"Cut a big paper mitten — grown-ups on scissors — and let your child decorate it with blue crayon, stickers, or torn paper. Hang it low where they can admire their work."},{"t":"Diamond Decorations","d":"Draw diamond shapes on a paper mitten and let your child color them with big crayons, mostly-inside counts. Trace the diamond with a finger — this month's shape, right on the craft."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Cozy is a feeling — this week we dress it, match it, and read it.","items":["Let your child put on their own jacket or shoes each morning — cheer every try.","Match sock or mitten pairs straight from the laundry basket.","Trace a big D — D is for down, dry, and cozy days.","End one day with a blanket-nest read-aloud in a whisper voice."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Winter Fun","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Snowball Toss","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Indoor Snowball Toss","d":"Crumple paper snowballs and toss them into a laundry basket, taking turns — my turn, your turn. Move the basket closer or farther to keep it just-right hard."},{"t":"Sock Snowball Kick","d":"Roll sock snowballs and kick them gently across the room into a goal between two cushions. Kicking a still target is real skill-building for two-year-old legs."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Tell About Play","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Play Reporter","d":"After playtime, help your child tell what happened in little sentences: 'I threw. It landed. I laughed.' Retelling turns doing into language."},{"t":"Quiet Q Game","d":"Whisper the Q sound — qu-qu-quiet — then tiptoe-quiet across the room and back. Loud, then quiet, on your signal. Volume control is self-control practice."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Winter Game Graph","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Vote and Count","d":"Ask everyone at home to pick a favorite winter game and stack one block per vote. Count the towers together — which is tallest? That is a graph, toddler-style."},{"t":"Melt Race Watch","d":"Set one ice cube in a sunny window and one in the shade and check back later — which melted first? Prediction plus patience equals a genuine science experiment."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Share the Fun","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Take Turn Games","d":"Play a simple back-and-forth game — roll the ball, stack a block each — narrating 'your turn, my turn.' Turn-taking at two is short and sweet; end while it is still fun."},{"t":"Games Everywhere","d":"Talk about how kids everywhere play in winter — some sled, some splash, some play ball. Then play your family's favorite together. Play is every child's language."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Snowflake Finale","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper Snowflake Color","d":"Fold and cut a simple paper snowflake — grown-ups on scissors — then let your child color it blue and tape it to the window. Every snowflake is different, just like us."},{"t":"Winter Book Finale","d":"End the month with a favorite winter read-aloud and let your child hold the book and turn the pages. Page-turning is tiny-hands work with a big literacy payoff."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Wrap up winter with play, turns, and one proud snowflake on the window.","items":["Play one 'your turn, my turn' game a day, and end while it is still fun.","Whisper the Q sound — qu-qu-quiet — then tiptoe to bed.","Vote on the family's favorite winter game and count the votes with blocks.","Hang a blue paper snowflake your child colored in the window."]}}]},"feb":{"theme":"Kindness & Friendship","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — What Is a Friend?","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Mirror a Friend","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Copycat Moves","d":"Stand face-to-face and be the leader — clap, stomp, wiggle, touch your toes — while your child copies you, then trade jobs. Copying a partner is how twos first practice being a friend."},{"t":"Guess My Face","d":"Make a happy, sad, or surprised face and let your child guess the feeling, then swap — they make one, you guess. Reading faces is the very first friendship skill."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Friend Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"A Friend Is Someone","d":"At snack time, take turns finishing the sentence 'A friend is someone who…' Offer easy answers — shares, hugs, plays — and cheer whatever your child adds. Talking about friends builds friend skills."},{"t":"Storybook Friends","d":"Read a favorite picture book together and point to the friends on each page. Ask 'who is playing?' Pointing and naming is big language work at two."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count Our Friends","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Teddy Head Count","d":"Line up three stuffed animals for a pretend playdate. Touch each one as you count — one, two, three. Touching while counting teaches twos that every friend gets one number."},{"t":"Photo Friend Hunt","d":"Open a family photo and point to each face you love. Count the faces together up to three or four, then name them. Familiar faces make counting feel like love."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Gentle Hands","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Soft or Scratchy","d":"Walk around touching things gently — a soft blanket, a scratchy doormat, a smooth table. Say 'gentle hands' as you go. Exploring textures teaches the light touch friends need."},{"t":"Pat the Bear","d":"Show your child how to give a teddy slow, gentle pats, then a soft hug. Practicing gentleness on a toy makes it easier with real friends and baby siblings."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Friendship Portrait","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Draw My Friend","d":"Tape paper to the table and let your child scribble a picture of a friend with big crayons. Ask who it is and write the name underneath — their words on paper feel like magic."},{"t":"Pink Heart Picture","d":"Draw a big heart — February's shape — and let your child fill it with pink scribbles. Say 'heart' and 'pink' as you color. Shapes and colors stick best inside happy moments."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Tuck these in your pocket — little friendship moments all week long.","items":["At pickup or dinner, ask 'who did you play with today?' and listen big.","Go on a heart hunt — find heart shapes on cards, pajamas, and snack boxes.","Count to three on fingers every time you wash hands together.","Point out pink things all week — pink is February's color."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Kind Words & Deeds","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Kindness Delivery","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Delivery Helper","d":"Give a two-step job: 'Take this sock to Daddy and say here you go.' Clap when it lands. Carrying and delivering makes kindness something a two-year-old can do with their whole body."},{"t":"Doorstep Surprise","d":"Help your child leave a scribbled drawing outside a family member's bedroom door, knock, and toddle away giggling. Surprising someone kindly feels wonderfully sneaky at two."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Kind Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Rrr Is Respect","d":"Practice February's letter R with a growly 'rrr — respect.' Then try kind words together: please, thank you, are you okay. The kind words your child hears from you become their own."},{"t":"Puppet Manners","d":"Slip a sock on your hand and let the puppet forget its manners. Your child gets to teach it to say please. Correcting a silly puppet is how twos rehearse kindness."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Kindness Jar","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Kindness Jar Count","d":"Set out a jar and drop in one big pasta piece each time someone in the family is kind. Count the pieces at bedtime — one, two, three. Watching kindness pile up is powerful."},{"t":"Seven Hearts Line","d":"Cut seven paper hearts — a grown-up scissors job — and let your child line them up while you count to seven together. Seven is February's number, a fun stretch past their steady three."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Bucket Filling","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Bucket Scoop","d":"At a bowl of water, stay within arm's reach while your child scoops cupfuls until it's full. Talk about full and empty — kind words fill people up the very same way."},{"t":"Cotton Ball Bucket","d":"Drop a cotton ball into a bowl for every hug or kind word this morning, squeezing and squishing as you go. Soft things in little hands make the idea of soft words real."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Heart Craft","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Torn Paper Heart","d":"Draw a big heart and let your child tear pink and red scraps to glue inside it. Tearing is terrific finger exercise, and the finished heart makes a proud little gift."},{"t":"Card for Someone","d":"Fold paper into a card and let your child scribble love with big crayons while you write their kind message inside. Ask 'who should we give it to?' and deliver it together."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Kind words at home this week — small, doable, every single day.","items":["Catch kindness out loud: 'You shared — that was kind.'","Practice the R sound — rrr — in respect, rabbit, and run.","Keep a kindness jar on the counter and count it each night.","Trade one thank-you at dinner — everyone thanks one person."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Working Together","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Team Blanket Play","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Blanket Parachute","d":"Hold two corners of a small blanket while your child holds the others, then bounce a rolled-up sock into the air together. Keeping the sock flying only works if you work together."},{"t":"Up and Under","d":"Play with February's letter U: lift the blanket UP high, then crawl UNDER before it floats down. Say 'uh — up, under' as you play. Position words plus wiggles equal toddler heaven."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Together Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"We Did It","d":"Do tiny jobs as a pair — zip a bag, push in a chair — and cheer 'we did it together!' Naming teamwork out loud helps a parallel-play two start noticing partners."},{"t":"Turn the Page","d":"Snuggle up with any picture book and share the jobs: you read the words, your child turns the pages. Sharing a book is a two-year-old's first great team project."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Team Tower","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Tower for Two","d":"Take turns stacking boxes or blocks — you place one, your child places one — counting each piece up to five. Then let it crash and study the tumble. Building together is math and teamwork in one."},{"t":"Cup Mountain","d":"Stack plastic cups into a little mountain, handing them over one at a time. Ask 'what happens if we bump it?' and find out. Predicting and testing is real toddler science."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Little Helpers","domains":["Social Studies","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Chore Buddies","d":"Pick one real family job — wiping the table, feeding the pet, matching socks — and do it side by side. Twos glow when their help is real, not pretend."},{"t":"Laundry Team","d":"Pass laundry from basket to bed together, piece by piece. Your child hands, you fold. Family jobs done as a pair teach twos they belong to a team called home."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Group Mural","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Family Mural","d":"Tape a big piece of paper to the floor and let everyone scribble on the same page with big crayons. Name colors and squiggles as you go — one artwork, many hands."},{"t":"Trace Our Hands","d":"Trace your hand, then your child's hand overlapping it, and color them in together. Talk about big hand, little hand — words for size grow right alongside the picture."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Teamwork travels — try these together moments at home.","items":["Say 'we did it together' every time you finish a job as a pair.","Practice the U sound — uh — in up, under, and umbrella.","Give one two-step direction a day: 'Get your cup and put it on the table.'","Build one tower together at bedtime and count the blocks."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Hearts & Helpers","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Helper Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Helper Marching Band","d":"March around the house doing helper jobs to a beat — stomp to the laundry, tiptoe to the bookshelf, hop to the shoes. Big movement makes helping feel like a game, not a chore."},{"t":"Wave to Helpers","d":"On a walk or drive, wave to the helpers you spot — mail carrier, trash truck, crossing guard. Name what each one does. Twos learn community by waving at it."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Thank You Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Vvv Is Valentine","d":"Buzz February's letter V on your lips — vvv — like valentine and van. Then practice a big warm thank-you for someone who helps your child every single day."},{"t":"Pretend Phone Thanks","d":"Help your child say one thank-you into a pretend phone — 'Thank you, Grandma' or 'Thank you, Doctor.' Rehearsing gratitude in play makes it come out easier in real life."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Heart Sort","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Big and Little Hearts","d":"Cut paper hearts in two sizes — a grown-up job — and let your child sort them into a big pile and a little pile. Sorting by one thing at a time is exactly right for two."},{"t":"Seven on the Door","d":"Tape the number 7 where your child can reach and touch it each morning while you count seven gentle pats on their head. February's number becomes a friendly face by Friday."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Squishy Hearts","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Play-Dough Hearts","d":"Roll pink play-dough into balls, squish them flat, and pinch them into hearts. Talk about squishy, soft, and flat — hands that squish today are hands getting ready to write."},{"t":"Heart Prints","d":"Press a cookie cutter or a folded cardboard heart into play-dough and peek at the print it leaves behind. Making marks and lifting them away is cause and effect a two can feel."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Valentines for Friends","domains":["Creative Expression","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Valentine Delivery","d":"Let your child scribble on folded paper valentines, then deliver one to each person in the house with a hug. Giving something they made grows a proud, generous heart."},{"t":"Feelings Faces Read","d":"Snuggle up with Your Feelings Matter, Mrs. Bear's own book, and make each face together — happy, sad, loved. Naming feelings is the deepest kindness a two can learn."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A love-filled send-off — easy heart moments for home.","items":["Deliver one homemade valentine to a family member you love.","Practice the V sound — vvv — in valentine, van, and vroom.","Name one helper you saw today and say what they do.","Squeeze in one extra snuggle-and-story before bed this week."]}}]},"mar":{"theme":"Things That Grow","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Seeds & Plants","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Grow Like Seeds","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Seed to Tree","d":"Curl up tiny on the floor like a seed, then grow slowly — sprout arms, stretch a stem, wave leafy fingers. Growing slow on purpose is wiggly practice in patience."},{"t":"I Am Growing","d":"Stand tall and cheer March's letter I together: 'I am growing.' Then stretch up on tiptoes as high as you both can reach. Twos love any game starring themselves."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Plant Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Root Stem Leaf","d":"Find a houseplant or a weed outside and gently touch as you name the parts — root, stem, leaf, flower. Real plants make new words stick better than any flashcard."},{"t":"Seed Story Time","d":"Read a picture book about a seed growing, pausing to ask 'what comes next?' Stories about growing give your two the words for what their own body is doing."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count the Seeds","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Pasta Seed Count","d":"Pretend big dried pasta pieces are giant seeds. Drop them into a cup one at a time, counting to five together. Dropping and counting is how two-year-old math takes root."},{"t":"Sort the Garden","d":"Set out two bowls and sort pretend seeds from pretend leaves — big pasta in one, torn green paper in the other. Sorting by one thing at a time is just right for two."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Foods That Grow","domains":["Social Studies","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Fridge Farm Tour","d":"Open the fridge together and find three foods that grew from seeds — apple, carrot, banana. Say 'a farmer grew this.' Food gets much more interesting when it has a story."},{"t":"Thank You, Farmers","d":"At a meal, point to something on the plate that grew and send a silly 'thank you, farmers' out the window together. Gratitude plus giggles is the two-year-old sweet spot."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Seed Collage","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Sticky Seed Picture","d":"Spread glue on paper and let your child press on big pasta seeds and torn-paper leaves. Name everything as it lands. Sticky art builds fingers and vocabulary at the same time."},{"t":"Purple Flower Scribble","d":"Draw a tall stem and let your child scribble a big purple bloom on top — purple is March's color. Say 'stem' and 'flower' as you work, then hang it low enough to pat."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Plant a little wonder at home this week.","items":["Plant one seed in a cup by a window and check it every morning.","Practice the I sound — i-i — in itch, in, and inchworm.","Name plant parts on your walk: stem, leaf, flower.","Count five pretend seeds into a cup before snack."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — In the Garden","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Garden Workout","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Dig Rake Water","d":"Call out garden moves and do them big — dig low, rake wide, water high on tiptoes. Switch speeds, slow then fast. Following changing directions is a toddler brain workout."},{"t":"X Marks the Spot","d":"Tape a big letter X on the floor and make it home base — hop to the X, dig at the X, nap on the X. March's letter X becomes a game they can stand on."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Garden Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Tool Talk","d":"Gather a spoon, a cup, and a pitcher and name each pretend garden tool's job — dig, scoop, water. Tools plus words teach twos how helpers get things done."},{"t":"Garden Picture Walk","d":"Look at a garden picture in any book or magazine and label everything you see — dirt, flower, bug, sun. Labeling pictures together now is reading readiness later."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Measure the Plant","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Block Tall","d":"Stack blocks in a tower next to a houseplant or a boot until they match its height, counting each block. Measuring with blocks turns math into something twos can grab."},{"t":"Tall and Small","d":"Line up a spoon, a bottle, and a broom, and ask 'which is tall? which is small?' Comparing sizes is early measuring — no numbers required yet."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Water Helper","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"One Cup of Care","d":"Let your child carry one small cup of water to a plant and pour it slowly, watching the soil turn dark. Caring for a living thing grows gentleness you can see."},{"t":"Drink Up, Plant","d":"Water a plant together, then peek under the leaves and whisper 'the roots are drinking.' Twos love knowing secret invisible things are happening right under their noses."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Paper Flower","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper Circle Bloom","d":"Cut a big paper circle — a grown-up job — and let your child scribble it into a flower and glue on torn-paper petals. Write their words about it on the back."},{"t":"Oval Petal Flower","d":"Draw oval petals — March's shape — around a circle and let your child color each one with big crayons. Say 'oval' as you go. Shapes learned inside art stick around."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Bring the garden home — no green thumb required.","items":["Give your child one watering job this week and keep it theirs.","Practice the X sound — ks — at the end of box and fox.","Find ovals around the house: eggs, spoons, soap.","Share one garden or growing story at bedtime."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Baby Animals","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Baby Animal Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Waddle and Hop","d":"Waddle like a duckling, hop like a bunny, and gallop like a foal around the living room. Moving like animals builds big muscles and big imaginations at the same time."},{"t":"Puppy Follow","d":"Crawl behind your child like a mama dog following her puppy, then trade who leads. Leading and following in play is gentle practice for both listening and confidence."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Mama and Baby","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Match the Babies","d":"Look at animal pictures and match mamas to babies — dog to puppy, cat to kitten, hen to chick. Ask 'where is the baby?' Matching pairs is thinking work dressed as play."},{"t":"Animal Sound Off","d":"Make a mama animal's big sound and let your child answer with the baby's tiny version — big MOO, little moo. Loud and soft, big and small: that's science little ears can do."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Count the Babies","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Three Little Chicks","d":"Line up three stuffed animals as babies and tuck them in one by one, counting as you go. Then recount to be sure nobody wiggled away. Counting the same set twice builds real number sense."},{"t":"Egg Carton Count","d":"Drop cotton-ball eggs into an egg carton, one per cup, counting up to five. One egg in one cup is early one-to-one matching — the root of all math."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Gentle with Babies","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Wrap and Rock","d":"Wrap a doll or teddy in a dish towel and practice holding it gently, patting and rocking. Nurturing play grows the soft skills twos need with pets and baby siblings."},{"t":"Zzz Little One","d":"Whisper March's letter Z — zzz — as you tuck baby animals in for a pretend family nap, then tiptoe away together. Quiet games teach twos their volume has a gentle setting."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Handprint Chick","domains":["Creative Expression","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Handprint Chick Art","d":"Paint your child's palm, press a handprint, and add eyes and a beak to hatch a chick. Washable paint, wipes ready. Twos are amazed their own hand made an animal."},{"t":"Baby Animal Story","d":"Snuggle up and read any baby-animal book, naming each mama and baby in your softest voices. Ask 'where is the kitten?' and let little fingers do the finding."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A week of soft, snuggly practice being gentle.","items":["Practice gentle pats on a stuffed animal before trying them on the cat.","Whisper the Z sound — zzz — at every pretend nap and real bedtime.","Match mamas to babies in books: dog-puppy, cat-kitten, duck-duckling.","Count three tuck-ins for three stuffed friends at bedtime."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Growing Me","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"How Tall","domains":["Physical Development","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"Doorframe Check","d":"Stand your child at the doorframe, mark their height with masking tape, and let them jump to touch it. Compare it to a grown-up's mark. Tall and small words come alive."},{"t":"Reach and Grow","d":"Play 'when I was a baby' with your bodies — curl up tiny, crawl, toddle, then stride like a big kid. Ending tall and proud tells the story of growing without a single page."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Baby to Big","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Baby Photo Talk","d":"Look at your child's baby photos and narrate: 'You were so tiny. Now you can run.' Twos adore the story of themselves — it builds language and a sturdy little identity."},{"t":"Now I Can","d":"Take turns finishing 'Now I can…' — jump, sing, climb, pour. Clap for each one. Naming what they can do teaches twos to see themselves as growing and capable."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Order the Photos","domains":["Approaches to Learning","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"First Baby, Then Big","d":"Lay out three photos — baby, one-year-old, now — and help your child put them in order. First, then, last. Sequencing their own story is thinking work with heart."},{"t":"Family Grew Too","d":"Show photos of grown-ups as babies and ask 'who is this?' The giggly surprise that Mama was little once teaches twos that everyone in the family grows."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"I Can Do It","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Pour It Myself","d":"Set out a small pitcher and cup and let your child pour their own water — within arm's reach, towel standing by. Spills are part of the science. Doing it myself is how confidence grows."},{"t":"Zip Snap Practice","d":"Lay out a jacket and let your child finish the zipper after you start it, or try one snap. One tiny self-help win a day adds up to a very capable two."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Growth Portrait","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Big Me Portrait","d":"Draw a big oval — March's shape — for a face and let your child add eyes, hair, and purple scribbles. Write 'I am growing' underneath and read it together, pointing at each word."},{"t":"Trace My Whole Self","d":"Trace your child's whole body on taped-together paper or a flattened box, then color it in together. Standing beside their own outline shows a two just how much of them there is."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Celebrate how far your little one has grown.","items":["Tell one 'when you were a baby' story at bedtime.","Let your child do one 'all by myself' job each morning.","Count to eight on the stairs — eight is March's number.","Play with all three March sounds: i-i, ks, and zzz."]}}]},"apr":{"theme":"Our Big Blue Earth","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Land & Water","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Land or Water","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Hop the Earth","d":"Lay out a blue towel for water and a green blanket for land. Call 'water' and swim your arms, call 'land' and stomp your feet. Listening for the switch is toddler brain gym."},{"t":"Animal Move Across","d":"Cross the room like water animals, then land animals — swish like a fish, then stomp like a bear. Big pretend movement plants the idea that different animals live in different places."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Blue Means Water","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Map Finger Trip","d":"Find a globe, a map, or a map picture in a book and let your child pat the blue parts — water — and the green parts — land. Our big blue Earth makes sense one pat at a time."},{"t":"Ocean Story Time","d":"Read any book with ocean or river pictures and name what you see — waves, fish, boat. Water words learned in your lap float right back up at bath time."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Sort the Animals","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Two Home Sort","d":"Set out a blue paper and a green paper and sort toy animals — fish and duck onto water, bear and cow onto land. Sorting by one rule is exactly right at two."},{"t":"Count the Swimmers","d":"Float a few bath toys and count them to three or four, touching each one. Then count the land animals waiting on the towel. Counting two little groups is early comparing."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Water Wonder","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Sink or Float","d":"Fill a bowl, stay within arm's reach, and test treasures — spoon, cork, crayon. Ask 'sink or float?' before each drop. Guessing first is the seed of real science."},{"t":"Wonder Walk","d":"Step outside and find one wonder — a puddle, a cloud, a worm — and just look at it together for a minute. Slowing down to marvel teaches twos that Earth is worth loving."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Little Blue Earth","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Earth Collage","d":"Cut a big paper circle — a grown-up job — and let your child glue on torn blue and green scraps to make their own Earth. Say 'this is our home' and hang it low enough to pat."},{"t":"Teal Scribble Sea","d":"Scribble a sea with teal and blue crayons — teal is April's color — and draw a few fish swimming through it. Name the color as you work. New color words need lots of repeats."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Bring our big blue Earth down to toddler size this week.","items":["Pat the blue (water) and green (land) on any map you pass.","Play sink-or-float at bath time — always within arm's reach.","Say 'teal' when you spot April's color on cups and clothes.","Read one water or ocean story at snuggle time."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Reduce, Reuse, Recycle","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Recycle Relay","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Bin Run","d":"Set the recycling bin across the room and let your child run each clean item over — one bottle, one box, one carton. Helping the family recycle makes a two feel importantly big."},{"t":"Carry for the Earth","d":"Make recycling time a two-person job: you hand each clean item over, your child carries it, and together you drop it in. Real jobs side by side teach twos that caring for Earth is what families do."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Three R Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Say Reuse","d":"Practice the big word 'reuse' while turning an empty box into something new — a hat, a garage, a drum. New words plus silly play equal words that stay."},{"t":"Bottle Shaker Band","d":"Drop big dried pasta into an empty bottle, screw the lid on tight, and shake along to a favorite song. One bottle reused is one Earth lesson your child can hear."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Sort and Count","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Paper or Plastic","d":"Set out two boxes and sort clean recycling together — paper in one, plastic in the other — counting each drop. Sorting real stuff by one rule is toddler math with a purpose."},{"t":"Spot the Nine","d":"Go looking for April's number 9 on cartons, clocks, and mailboxes, tracing it with one small finger when you find it. Numbers spotted in the wild feel like treasure."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Proud Tidy-Uppers","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Beat the Song Cleanup","d":"Play one song and race to tuck every toy back home before it ends, cheering the finish together. Cleaning up to music turns responsibility into a game twos ask to play."},{"t":"One Spot Shine","d":"Give your child a damp cloth and one job — wipe the little table until it shines. Step back and admire it together. Pride in a job well done grows helpers for life."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Recycled Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Box Robot","d":"Let your child scribble a face and buttons on a clean cereal box to make a box robot. Name each part together — eyes, tummy, feet. Turning trash into a toy is toddler magic."},{"t":"Cardboard Canvas","d":"Flatten a cereal box and let it be today's canvas for big teal and green scribbles. Talk about how the box got a second job. Art and reuse in one happy sitting."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Little green habits start in tiny hands.","items":["Let your child drop one clean item in the recycling bin every day.","Turn one box into a toy before it reaches the bin.","Trace the number 9 on a carton with one small finger.","Read a story, then name one thing in it we could reuse."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Weather & Sky","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Weather Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Sun Rain Wind Dance","d":"Call the weather and move like it — arms in a big sun circle, fingers raining down, spinning like wind. Freeze between rounds. Listening, then moving is two-year-old self-control practice."},{"t":"Storm Stomp","d":"Stomp big thunder feet, then shrink down to quiet drizzle tiptoes — loud to soft and back again. Playing with loud and quiet gives twos a body-sized volume knob."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Sky Check","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Yellow Sun Stretch","d":"When the sun is out, stretch both arms up in a big letter Y and cheer 'y-y-yellow sun' together. On gray days, hunt for one yellow thing indoors instead. April's letter comes with its own morning stretch."},{"t":"Cloud Watch","d":"Lie back and watch the clouds drift for a few minutes, asking 'is it moving? is it big?' Wondering out loud together is exactly how scientific minds get their start."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Chart the Weather","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Sticker Sky Chart","d":"Tape up a paper and draw a sun, cloud, or raindrop on it each morning this week. On Friday, count which one won. A homemade chart makes the sky countable."},{"t":"Raindrop Count","d":"On a rainy day, watch drops race down the window and count them to five as they reach the bottom. Watching and counting drops turns a gray day into a game."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Calm in Storms","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Pot Drum Rain","d":"Drum fingertips on an upside-down pot — light drizzle, then big storm, then slow back to quiet. Ending gentle and slow shows twos how to bring big feelings down softly."},{"t":"Cozy Storm Fort","d":"Build a blanket fort and stock it with books and a flashlight for stormy days, then practice once with pretend thunder. Having a cozy plan turns scary weather into snuggle weather."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Moon and Sky Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Crescent Moon Craft","d":"Draw a big crescent — April's shape — and let your child fill it with scribbles, then glue on cotton-ball clouds. Say 'crescent moon' as you work. Shape words learned in art stick."},{"t":"Goodnight Moon Time","d":"At bedtime, find the moon out the window, then read a nighttime or moon book together. Ask 'is the moon a crescent tonight?' Sky watching plus a story is the softest landing."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"This week, the sky is the lesson plan.","items":["Do the arms-up Y stretch and greet the sun each morning.","Practice the Y sound — y-y — in yellow, yes, and yawn.","Look for the crescent moon after dinner and name its shape.","Keep a cozy-storm plan ready: blanket, book, flashlight, snuggles."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Caring for Our Earth","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Earth Helper Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Litter Patrol","d":"On a walk, let your child point out litter while you pick it up with a bag over your hand, counting the pieces together. Twos who help clean the world start to feel it is theirs to protect."},{"t":"Watering Walk","d":"Walk your outdoor plants or windowsill pots with a small cup, giving each one a drink. Helping green things live is Earth care sized exactly right for two."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Earth Care Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"I Help the Earth","d":"Take turns finishing 'I care for the Earth by…' — turning off lights, putting trash in the bin, watering plants. Saying it out loud helps a two see themselves as a helper."},{"t":"Earth Book Snuggle","d":"Read an Earth or nature book together and name every living thing you spot — tree, bird, bug, flower. Loving the Earth starts with knowing its names."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Green Deeds Count","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Green Deeds Chart","d":"Draw a leaf on a chart each time your family does something kind for the Earth, counting the leaves each night up to five. Watching good deeds grow is math with meaning."},{"t":"Nine Pats for Earth","d":"Tape the number 9 by the light switch and give it nine gentle pats while chanting 'lights off.' April's number turns a green habit into a giggle."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Lights and Water Off","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Off Switch Hero","d":"Make your child the family's official light-turner-offer when you leave a room. Watch it go dark and say 'we saved power.' Cause and effect plus pride in one little flick."},{"t":"Drip Stop Watch","d":"Turn the faucet to a trickle, then let your child twist it off tight and listen for the quiet. Talk about saving water for the fish. Small hands love big responsibilities."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Earth Day Poster","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Our Earth Poster","d":"Make an Earth Day poster with teal, blue, and green scribbles, gluing on leaves gathered from a walk. Write your child's words about Earth across the top and read them back together."},{"t":"Letter Review Art","d":"Write Y and a few letters from your child's name in big bubble shapes and let them scribble each one full of color. Naming letters inside art keeps review playful, never like drill work."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Send the month off with a little Earth love at home.","items":["Give your child one 'off switch' job — lights or faucet.","Count nine pats on the number 9 whenever you spot one.","Collect fallen leaves on a walk to glue into art later.","Reread this month's favorite Earth story and say goodnight to the moon."]}}]},"may":{"theme":"On the Move","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Things That Go","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Vroom and Zoom","domains":["Physical Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Living Room Road Trip","d":"Hand your two-year-old a paper-plate steering wheel and drive around the house together — fast, slow, and stop. Name each pretend place you visit. New words stick best when the whole body is moving."},{"t":"Beep, Choo, Vroom","d":"Look at pictures of a car, a train, and a plane in a book or on your phone. Make each sound together and let your child copy you. Sound play builds the little mouth muscles that talking needs."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Count and Sort","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Three-Car Lineup","d":"Line up three toy cars and count them slowly — one, two, three. Then let your child park them in a shoebox garage one at a time. Counting a small number well beats racing to ten."},{"t":"Big Rig, Little Rig","d":"Gather toy vehicles, or use shoes as pretend cars, and sort them into a big pile and a little pile together. Sorting by just one thing at a time is real two-year-old math."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"My Turn, Your Turn","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Ticket, Please","d":"Play bus driver — your child hands you a paper ticket, you say thank you and climb aboard a couch cushion, then swap jobs. Tiny scripts like this teach turn-taking without a single lecture."},{"t":"Wheels on the Bus Duet","d":"Sing The Wheels on the Bus and let your child pick each verse — wipers, horn, or babies. Choosing keeps them in the driver's seat of the song, and repetition grows language."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Build It, Drive It","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Box Car Builder","d":"Set a cardboard box on the floor, tape on paper-plate wheels together, and let your child climb in for a push around the room. A good box beats the toy store most days."},{"t":"Play-Dough Roads","d":"Roll play-dough into long snake roads and drive a chunky toy car down them. All that squeezing and rolling builds the hand muscles that will hold a crayon soon."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Story Engines","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Freight Train Read","d":"Snuggle up with Freight Train, Little Blue Truck, or any wheels book and let your child point to what is moving on each page. Pointing and naming together is early reading, plain and simple."},{"t":"What Makes It Go","d":"Give a toy car one gentle push, then one big push, and watch how far it rolls each time. Say it out loud — you pushed hard, it went far. That is cause and effect your child can see."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Little on-the-go moments for a family on the move.","items":["Count three cars, trucks, or bikes out loud on your next drive.","Tape a masking-tape road across the floor for five minutes of quiet driving.","Sing The Wheels on the Bus at bath time and let your child pick the verses.","Say the sound before the vehicle appears — I hear a truck… there it is."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — On Land","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Cars, Trains, Bikes","domains":["Physical Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Two-Person Train","d":"Hold on at the waist and chug around the house in a little train, calling all aboard at every room. Starting and stopping on cue is big-muscle listening practice."},{"t":"Wheels in Our World","d":"From the window or on a short walk, spot things with wheels — stroller, bus, bike, wagon. Talk about who is riding and where they might be going. That is your child's first look at community."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Fast and Slow","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Fast Feet, Slow Feet","d":"Call out fast and slow while you both march, stomp, or tip-toe across the room. Opposites land in the body first and the words follow right behind."},{"t":"Near and Far Toss","d":"Set a laundry basket close and toss rolled socks in, then take two steps back and try again from far. Near and far are math words your two-year-old can feel."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Red Light Rules","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Red Light, Green Light","d":"Hold up a red paper circle for stop and a green one for go while your child drives or runs. Stopping on a signal is self-control in disguise — keep the rounds short and cheerful."},{"t":"Buckle Up Bear","d":"Buckle a stuffed animal into a box car seat and talk about how we keep our bodies safe in the car. Twos love keeping their babies safe, and it makes the rule feel kind."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Tell the Trip","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Where We Went","d":"After any errand, retell it together in three tiny steps — we rode, we shopped, we came home. Retelling their own day builds memory and story sense at the same time."},{"t":"Little Blue Truck Read","d":"Read Little Blue Truck or another friendly road story and beep, moo, and croak along together. Books about helping friends plant seeds of kindness while the truck sounds do the language work."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Road Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"Sticky Road Collage","d":"Stick strips of tape or glued paper onto a big sheet as roads, then let your child drive a finger-car along each one. Count the roads together — one, two, three."},{"t":"Rainbow Car Tracks","d":"Dip a toy car's wheels in a dab of washable paint and roll tracks across paper, one rainbow color at a time. Name each color as it rolls — this month we love the whole rainbow."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Quick land-travel games for driveway, hallway, and car line.","items":["Play one round of red light, green light on the way to the car.","Let your child buckle a stuffed animal before you buckle them.","Retell the day in three steps at tuck-in — we woke, we played, we snuggled.","Spot sign shapes on your drive — circles, triangles, even five-sided pentagons."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — On Water & Air","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Row and Fly","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Blanket Boat Rowing","d":"Sit facing each other on a blanket boat, hold hands, and rock while you sing Row, Row, Row Your Boat. Rocking together is rhythm, balance, and bonding all in one song."},{"t":"Airplane Arms","d":"Stretch arms wide and swoop around the room together, landing softly on a pillow runway. Add one slow landing and one zippy takeoff for giggles and gross-motor work."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Float or Sink","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"Load the Boat","d":"Float a plastic lid or bowl boat in a shallow pan and load it with spoons, one at a time, until it tips — stay within arm's reach the whole time. Counting the cargo as the boat wobbles is math and science in the same splash."},{"t":"Count the Boats","d":"Float two or three plastic cups in the sink and count them together, staying within arm's reach. Then one boat sails away behind your back — count again. Small numbers, big thinking."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Brave New Tries","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Walk the Plank","d":"Lay a masking-tape line or a couch-cushion path and cheer your little captain across, holding a hand if they want one. Say it out loud — that was brave. Naming courage grows it."},{"t":"Shin Airplane Ride","d":"Lie on your back, rest your child tummy-down on your shins, hold hands, and fly them gently like a plane. New sensations plus your steady grip build trust in trying."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Water and Air Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Boats and Planes Book","d":"Read any book with boats or planes and point together — sail, wing, splash, sky. Two or three juicy travel words, repeated all week, is how a two-year-old builds a sentence."},{"t":"Huff-Puff Sailboat","d":"Float a plastic cup in a shallow pan and blow it across like wind in a sail, staying within arm's reach. Air you cannot see just moved a boat — and big breaths calm big feelings, too."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Paper Boats","domains":["Creative Expression","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Fold-and-Float Boat","d":"Fold a simple paper boat — you make the folds, your child presses each crease flat — then float it in the sink within arm's reach. Watching their own boat float is pure two-year-old pride."},{"t":"Sky and Sea Scribbles","d":"Tape paper to the table and scribble blue waves along the bottom and puffy clouds up top with big crayons. Saying top and bottom while you draw sneaks position words into art time."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Boats, planes, and brave little tries — all before bedtime.","items":["Load a lid boat with bath toys until it tips — always within arm's reach.","Sing Row, Row, Row Your Boat with a gentle rock before bed.","Zoom airplane arms down the hallway to make cleanup feel like flying.","Count the bath-cup boats — one, two, three — then let one sail away."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — How I Move","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Run, Jump, Spin","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Three Move Stations","d":"Set three stations — jump by the pillow, spin by the couch, run to the door — and call them out one at a time. Two-step directions plus big movement is a perfect twos combination."},{"t":"Animal Move Copy","d":"Take turns being a hopping bunny, a stomping bear, and a slithering snake. Copying a movement they just watched builds body control and attention in one silly minute."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Count My Jumps","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Jump and Count","d":"Hold hands and count each jump out loud — aim for three, then try for five. Counting a real action their body just did makes numbers mean something."},{"t":"Tape-Line Tightrope","d":"Walk a masking-tape line heel to toe, counting steps as you go. Balance and counting take turns using the same busy little brain."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"I Can Move","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"I Did It Cheer","d":"Pick one just-hard-enough move — a big step off the bottom stair, a long jump over a sock river — and cheer the try either way. Saying I did it out loud builds a can-do voice inside."},{"t":"Action Word Calls","d":"Call out one action word at a time — stomp, clap, reach, wiggle — and do it together. Verbs are the engines of sentences, and twos learn them best in motion."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Shadow Moves","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Shadow Dance","d":"On a sunny patch of sidewalk, wave, stomp, and spin while your shadows copy every move. Then step into the shade and ask where they went. That is real science wondering."},{"t":"How Neighbors Move","d":"Watch from the window or a front step and name all the ways people are moving — walking, biking, pushing a stroller, riding a bus. Every body is on the move somewhere."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Dance and Paint","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Music Scribble Dance","d":"Play a song and scribble to the beat with big rainbow crayons — fast music means fast scribbles. When the music stops, the crayons freeze. Art, listening, and wiggles all get their turn."},{"t":"Feelings Moves Read","d":"Read Your Feelings Matter and act out each feeling with your whole body — a happy jump, a sleepy slump, a proud stretch. Moving a feeling helps a two-year-old name it next time."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Big-muscle minutes that wire little brains for learning.","items":["Count five jumps together before breakfast.","Have a thirty-second freeze dance while dinner cooks.","Cheer one brave new move today — say you did it together.","Count all ten toes at bath time — twos love the big finish."]}}]},"jun":{"theme":"Sun, Sand & Splash","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — At the Beach","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Tip-Toe Beach","domains":["Physical Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Hot Sand Dash","d":"Pretend the rug is hot beach sand — tip-toe across fast, then flop onto a towel beach blanket saying hot, hot, hot. Tip-toe walking builds balance and strong little legs."},{"t":"Beach Word Bag","d":"Drop a towel, sunglasses, a cup, and a sun hat into a bag. Pull out one at a time and name it together. A handful of beach words, repeated all week, is how twos build sentences."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Shell Sorting","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Big Shell, Little Shell","d":"Sort big and little shells — or big spoons and little spoons — into two bowls. Sorting by one thing at a time is exactly the math a two-year-old brain is building."},{"t":"Three Sand Scoops","d":"Set out a bowl of dry oats or rice sand and count three scoops into a cup together, staying close while they play. Scooping is measuring, and measuring is math."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Relaxed and Happy","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Beach Blanket Chill","d":"Lie on a towel side by side, sunglasses on, and take three slow beach breaths together. Say the word — this is relaxed. Naming a calm feeling, like in Your Feelings Matter, gives them a tool for later."},{"t":"Sprinkle Sand Picture","d":"Squeeze glue squiggles on paper, sprinkle salt or cornmeal over them, and shake off the extra. Instant sandy beach art, and the sprinkle-and-shake is fine-motor gold."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Beach Pretend","domains":["Approaches to Learning","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Pack the Beach Bag","d":"Pack a pretend beach bag using two-step directions — get the hat, put it in the bag. Packing is planning, and planning is one of the biggest skills hiding inside play."},{"t":"Lifeguard on Duty","d":"Line up the stuffed animals for a swim while your child sits in the lifeguard chair keeping everyone safe. Talk about how lifeguards are the helpers who watch over the water."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Wave Reading","domains":["Language & Literacy","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Ocean Book Snuggle","d":"Snuggle up with Hello Ocean or any beach book and make the wave sound together on every page — shhh, shhh. Sound effects turn a listener into a reader-in-training."},{"t":"Blanket Wave Jumps","d":"Ripple a blanket low along the floor like a rolling wave while your child jumps over it. Jumping on cue is timing, listening, and leg power in one giggly game."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A little beach day hiding inside every ordinary day.","items":["Tip-toe across the hot sand from the bath to the towel tonight.","Take three slow beach breaths together before nap.","Name one beach word a day — sand, wave, shell, towel, sun.","Read a beachy book and make the wave sound — shhh, shhh."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — In the Water","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Swim Those Arms","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Dry-Land Swimming","d":"Lie tummy-down on the floor side by side and practice big swim arms and kicky feet. Tummy-down play strengthens the shoulders and core that every big skill sits on."},{"t":"Fish Handprint","d":"Press a painted handprint on paper, turn it sideways, and add one eye — a handprint fish. Let your child scribble aqua water all around it with a big crayon."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Pour and Measure","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Cup-to-Cup Pouring","d":"Set two measuring cups in a shallow pan of water and pour back and forth, staying within arm's reach. Full and empty are math words your child can feel with their hands."},{"t":"Which Holds More","d":"Give a big cup and a little cup at the sink and pour from one into the other, within arm's reach. Watch the overflow surprise — that spill is a volume lesson, not a mess."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Water Table Manners","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Side-by-Side Splash","d":"Set out two bowls of water and two spoons — yours and theirs — and play side by side, within arm's reach. Parallel play is how twos practice being together before playing together."},{"t":"Wash the Babies","d":"Wash the waterproof toys gently with a drop of soap and a cloth, staying close by the water. We take care of our things — little caring jobs grow kindness."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Water Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Splash, Drip, Pour","d":"Narrate bath or sink play with juicy words — splash, drip, pour, squeeze — then pause and let your child hand one back to you. Rich words plus real water makes vocabulary stick."},{"t":"Warm or Cool","d":"Set out one bowl of warm water and one of cool, and touch each together, staying within arm's reach. Warm, cool — comparing with the senses is a two-year-old's first science lab."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Water Around Us","domains":["Social Studies","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Where Water Lives","d":"Take a little house tour and find where water lives — the faucet, the tub, the hose, the fridge. Mapping their own home is a two-year-old's first geography."},{"t":"Aqua Color Hunt","d":"Show your child aqua — the blue-green beach-water color — then hunt the house for anything close. Scribble an aqua picture after with big crayons. Color naming grows describing words."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Pouring, splashing, and learning — always within arm's reach.","items":["Give five minutes of cup-and-spoon play at bath time — stay within arm's reach.","Let your child wash one plastic toy while you wash the dishes.","Use three juicy water words today — splash, drip, pour.","Hunt for aqua, the blue-green beach color, on cups and clothes."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Sun & Sky","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Sunshine Chase","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Chase and Freeze","d":"Chase each other in the sunny part of the yard or room, then freeze the moment you both reach the shade. Go and stop on cue is self-control dressed up as a game."},{"t":"Sunshine Sway Song","d":"Sing You Are My Sunshine with a slow sway, your child on your hip or lap. A calm song from a favorite person is the original feel-better tool."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Shadow Science","domains":["Scientific Inquiry","Mathematical Thinking"],"opts":[{"t":"Big Shadow, Little Shadow","d":"Stand together in the sun and compare — whose shadow is big, whose is little? Check again later and see if they changed. Comparing sizes is measuring without a ruler."},{"t":"Count the Clouds","d":"Lie on a blanket and count clouds together, up to three or five. Ask what each one looks like and take any answer — a dog, a pancake, a shoe. Looking up counts as science."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Calm in the Shade","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Shade Rest Nest","d":"Build a little blanket nest in a shady spot and rest there with a lovey and a favorite book. A shady pause in the middle of a big sunny day shows little bodies how good slowing down can feel."},{"t":"Sunscreen Dots Practice","d":"Dot pretend sunscreen on arms and cheeks and rub, rub, rub it in together before the real thing. Self-help steps go smoother when they got to be a game first."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Sky Words","domains":["Language & Literacy","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Feel the Day","d":"Step outside for ten seconds together and feel the morning — hot, breezy, sticky, cool. Hand over the words as your child notices. Weather you can feel on your skin teaches better than any picture."},{"t":"Sunny Book Time","d":"Read any sunny-day picture book and hunt for the sun, sky, and clouds on each page. Pointing and naming while you read is exactly how early readers grow."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Sun and Sky Art","domains":["Creative Expression","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Scarf Cloud Dance","d":"Toss a light scarf or cloth napkin up like a drifting cloud and catch it before it lands. Tracking and catching something slow builds eyes and hands that work as a team."},{"t":"Paper-Plate Sunshine","d":"Tear yellow paper into strips and glue them around a paper plate as sun rays. Tearing is terrific finger strength, and every crooked ray makes it theirs."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Sunny-day science and shady-spot calm for busy families.","items":["Find your shadows on the way to the car and wave hello.","Do a one-minute cloud watch and let your child point to the biggest one.","Practice pretend sunscreen dots before the real ones — rub, rub, rub.","Sing You Are My Sunshine as this week's wake-up song."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Summer Play","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Backyard Games","domains":["Physical Development","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Sock Ball Relay","d":"Pile rolled socks at one end of the room and a basket at the other, then carry them over one at a time. One-at-a-time is a real rule to follow, and following it feels like winning."},{"t":"Summer Follow-the-Leader","d":"Lead a parade of summer moves — swim arms, jump the waves, march in the sunshine — then let your child lead. Being the leader is a big, proud job for a two-year-old."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Graph Our Fun","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Block Tower Vote","d":"Ask which was more fun today — bubbles or ball — and stack one block on a picture of each favorite thing all week. By Friday, the tallest tower shows the winner. That is a two-year-old's first graph."},{"t":"Ten Toes, One Nose","d":"Count all ten toes, then tap one little nose — ten toes and one nose makes eleven. It is a giggly first hello to this month's big number."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Share the Fun","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Everyone Plays Ball","d":"Sit in a circle with whoever is home and roll the ball to each person, saying their name first. Everyone gets a turn — that is what makes a family game feel fair."},{"t":"Teddy Bear Picnic","d":"Spread a blanket and invite every stuffed animal to a pretend picnic where everyone gets a plate. Including all the friends, even the raggedy ones, is sharing practice in disguise."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Tell Summer Stories","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Best Part Chat","d":"At dinner, ask about the best part of today and offer two choices if they need help — the bubbles or the picnic? Talking about their own day builds memory and conversation turns."},{"t":"Silly Ocean Read","d":"Read Commotion in the Ocean or any silly summer book and giggle at the animals together. Laughing over the same page is connection, and connection is what makes books beloved."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Memory Painting","domains":["Creative Expression","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Water Painting","d":"Hand over a big brush and a cup of water and paint the porch, fence, or sidewalk. Watch the strokes slowly disappear in the sun — where did the water go? Free art, real science."},{"t":"Summer Memory Colors","d":"Ask your child to draw something fun from this week with big crayons, then write their exact words along the bottom. Their scribble plus their words equals their very first summer memory book page."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Easy summer-play moments to squeeze into the in-between times.","items":["Play one round of follow-the-leader on the way inside.","Count ten toes and one nose — that makes eleven.","Set out a big brush and a cup of water to paint the porch.","Ask about the best part of today at tuck-in."]}}]},"jul":{"theme":"Imagination Station","weeks":[{"label":"Week 1 — Once Upon a Time","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Act It Out","domains":["Physical Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Three Bears Stomp","d":"Act out the three bears together — big bear stomps, middle bear walks, baby bear tip-toes. Playing a story with the whole body helps twos hold the words in their heads."},{"t":"Story Voice Read","d":"Read a well-loved book with big silly voices and pause before the last word of favorite lines so your child can shout it. Filling in the blank is a real early-reading skill."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"First, Next, Last","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Snack Story Order","d":"Narrate snack time as a story — first we wash hands, next we eat, last we wipe up. Order words are the bones of both math and storytelling, and snack happens every day anyway."},{"t":"Three-Picture Lineup","d":"Draw three quick stick pictures of the bedtime routine — bath, book, bed — and put them in order together. Twos love bossing the pictures into their right places."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Feelings in Stories","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"How Does Bear Feel","d":"Pause mid-story and ask how the character feels — happy or sad — then make the face together, just like the check-ins in Your Feelings Matter. Naming feelings in a book makes them easier to name in real life."},{"t":"Puppet Feelings Show","d":"Slip on a sock puppet who feels very happy, then very grumpy, and let your child guess each feeling. Puppets can feel big things safely, and twos love telling them it will be okay."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Story Cave","domains":["Creative Expression","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Blanket Fort Theater","d":"Drape a blanket over two chairs, crawl in with a flashlight, and tell a tiny tale in the glow. Lights on, lights off, shadows on the walls — cozy storytelling with a side of science."},{"t":"Draw-Your-Own Tale","d":"Hand over big crayons, ask for a story picture, and write their exact words underneath when they tell you about it. Their scribbles plus their words makes them the author."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Story Friends","domains":["Social Studies","Physical Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Neighborhood Story Walk","d":"On a short walk, make up tiny stories about the world you pass — where is that mail truck going, who will get the letters? Wondering about neighbors and helpers is early social studies."},{"t":"Helper Hero Moves","d":"Act out community helpers with big movements — drive the fire truck, stir the soup, check teddy's heartbeat. Pretend jobs build real vocabulary about the people in your town."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Once-upon-a-time moments for every corner of the day.","items":["Let your child turn the pages at story time — every page, their job.","Act out one page of tonight's book together.","Use first, next, last words during one routine today.","Build a five-minute blanket fort for a flashlight story."]}},{"label":"Week 2 — Make-Believe & Dress-Up","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Move Like Characters","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Stomp, Flutter, Creep","d":"Call out a character and become it together — stomp like a dragon, flutter like a fairy, creep like a sneaky cat. Switching movements on cue is body control and pretending at once."},{"t":"Towel Cape Flyer","d":"Tuck a towel cape into the back of your child's shirt collar and let your hero zoom the hallway while you watch. A cape turns an ordinary run into a story."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Sort the Costumes","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Hats Here, Shoes There","d":"Dump the dress-up basket or a laundry pile and sort hats in one spot, shoes in another. Sorting by one attribute is the exact math job a two-year-old brain is hiring for."},{"t":"A Dozen Props","d":"Drop one chunky prop into each cup of an egg carton until all twelve spots are full, counting the first three out loud together. Filling a dozen is a friendly hello to this month's number."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"I Can Be Anything","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Who Am I Today","d":"Offer a chef's bowl, a builder's toy hammer, or a doctor's teddy patient and ask who they want to be. Talk about what that helper does. Trying on jobs is trying on confidence."},{"t":"Mirror Me Pretend","d":"Stand at the mirror in costume and ask who you see. Wave, bow, and take a superhero pose together. Seeing themselves as the character makes the pretending feel true."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Talk the Part","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Phone a Friend","d":"Hand over a block phone and call each other from across the room — hello, how are you, bye-bye. Pretend phone calls are turn-taking talk practice with zero pressure."},{"t":"Tea Party Script","d":"Pour pretend tea and trade little lines — more tea, please; thank you; so yummy. Tiny scripts give twos the polite words before real life asks for them."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Make a Puppet","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Sock Puppet Pal","d":"Turn a sock into a puppet pal and let it do the talking — it can ask about lunch, sing a hello song, or get things hilariously wrong. Children often talk more to a puppet than a person."},{"t":"The Amazing Box","d":"Hand your child a real empty box and watch what it becomes — a car, a house, a rocket. If you have Not a Box, read it together first. Follow their idea, not yours — that is imagination taking the wheel."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"A dress-up week made from things you already own.","items":["Start a dress-up basket with old hats, big shirts, and a towel cape.","Ask who are you today and play along for two minutes.","Count snack crackers into an egg carton — a dozen little spots.","Have a pretend phone chat from across the room."]}},{"label":"Week 3 — Art & Music","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Dance It Out","domains":["Physical Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Fast Song, Slow Song","d":"Play one zippy song and one slow one, and match your dancing to each. Moving fast and slow on purpose builds the body control twos are working so hard on."},{"t":"Pots-and-Pans March","d":"Hand out a pot and a wooden spoon and march the hallway as a two-person band. Keeping a beat with the whole body is early music and early rhythm for reading."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Patterns and Sounds","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Clap-Stomp Pattern","d":"Start a simple pattern — clap, stomp, clap, stomp — and invite your child to join the beat. Patterns are pre-math, and this one needs nothing but hands and feet."},{"t":"Water Cup Chimes","d":"Fill three plastic cups with different amounts of water and tap each with a spoon, staying within arm's reach. More water, deeper sound — that is sound science a two-year-old can hear."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"Art Shows Feelings","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"Happy Colors, Grumpy Colors","d":"Scribble how today feels with big crayons — maybe sunny yellow for happy, thundery gray for grumpy. Putting a feeling on paper is a gentle first step toward putting it into words."},{"t":"Squish-and-Say Dough","d":"Squeeze play-dough together and name what you are squishing out — squish the grumpies, pat the happies. Strong little hands and steadier big feelings, all in one lump."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"Describe Our Art","domains":["Language & Literacy","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Tell Me About It","d":"Instead of asking what their picture is, say tell me about your picture — then write their exact words on the back. Open questions invite real talk; labels shut it down."},{"t":"Picture Book Art Hunt","d":"Read a favorite picture book slowly and hunt the artwork together — find something purple on this page, find something tiny. Lingering over pictures builds looking-closely muscles."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Purple Studio","domains":["Creative Expression","Scientific Inquiry"],"opts":[{"t":"Make Purple Magic","d":"Squeeze a dab of red and a dab of blue paint on paper — or knead two play-dough colors — and mix until purple appears. Watching a brand-new color arrive is honest-to-goodness chemistry."},{"t":"Big Box Mural","d":"Flatten a cardboard box, tape it down, and let your child crayon a great big mural across it. Giant paper means giant arm movements, and giant arm movements build writing muscles."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Little artists and loud musicians, welcome home.","items":["Tape artwork at your child's height and take a two-person gallery walk.","Say tell me about your picture instead of what is it.","Hunt for purple on every page of tonight's book.","March to one song with a pot-lid drum before dinner."]}},{"label":"Week 4 — Dream Big","days":[{"day":"Monday","focus":"Superhero Moves","domains":["Physical Development","Social & Emotional Development"],"opts":[{"t":"Hero Training Course","d":"Set up hero training — crawl under the chair, leap the pillow, land in a strong pose. Say it as they finish: so strong, so brave. Words like that become the voice inside."},{"t":"Strong and Kind","d":"Give your superhero helping missions — fly a toy back to its bin, deliver a cup to the table. Heroes help. Pairing strong with kind is character building at two."}]},{"day":"Tuesday","focus":"Plan Big Ideas","domains":["Mathematical Thinking","Approaches to Learning"],"opts":[{"t":"Tall Tower Dream","d":"Build the tallest tower you two can manage, counting blocks as they stack — one, two, three, more. When it tumbles, cheer and rebuild. Trying again is the real lesson."},{"t":"Count Our Ideas","d":"Ask what should we play and hold up one finger for each idea — one, two, three ideas. Then pick together. Their ideas getting counted tells them their ideas count."}]},{"day":"Wednesday","focus":"When I Grow Up","domains":["Language & Literacy","Social Studies"],"opts":[{"t":"Grown-Up Talk","d":"Ask what your child wants to be when they grow up and accept every answer — a doctor, a puppy, a truck. Talk about what that one does all day. Big dreams start as silly answers."},{"t":"Fix-It Pretend","d":"Grab a toy hammer or a big spoon and go fix things around the house together — tap the table leg, twist the doorknob, all fixed. Pretend work teaches what real workers do."}]},{"day":"Thursday","focus":"My Ideas Matter","domains":["Social & Emotional Development","Creative Expression"],"opts":[{"t":"You Pick, We Play","d":"For ten minutes, your child picks the game and you simply follow their lead — no fixing, no steering. Being followed tells a two-year-old their ideas are worth having."},{"t":"Invention Junk Build","d":"Tape a couple of boxes and a paper-towel tube into an invention and ask what it does. Whatever they say, it does exactly that. Builders first, engineers later."}]},{"day":"Friday","focus":"Dream Drawing","domains":["Creative Expression","Language & Literacy"],"opts":[{"t":"Dream Big Drawing","d":"Ask your child to draw their big dream with big crayons, then write their words along the bottom exactly as they say them. Hang it low where they can visit it."},{"t":"Magnificent Bedtime Read","d":"Read The Most Magnificent Thing or any keep-trying story at bedtime and talk about one big thing you will each try tomorrow. Dreams grow best right before sleep."}]}],"homeden":{"title":"The Home Den — This Week","lead":"Little dreamers with big ideas — here is how to water them.","items":["Let your child lead ten minutes of play — they pick, you follow.","Ask what do you want to be at dinner and dream along.","Save one cardboard box for an invention build.","Write their exact words on their drawings — instant author pride."]}}]}};